the Licensor. Redelivery: torrents.empornium.me has very limited storage for custom torrents, so if you are notified by us that one or more licensed torrents that you requested are ready for download, it is your responsibility to immediately retrieve them before they are deleted from our web server. (Requests to re-upload or resend licensed custom torrents that you have lost or neglected to timely retrieve, if still available, will incur a redelivery use fee surcharge of twenty-five dollars per torrent, not subject to fee waiver.) In the event that you encounter any diffi','2012-08-04 12:53:43'),(67,1,4,'irc_dummies',0,'01. IRC for Dummies','Basic guide for our IRC Channels','The easiest and fastest way to join the fun or get help on IRC is to use the IRC link at the top of your screen:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-6373_5024677D.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\n[b][color=#FF0000]You do not have to worry about anonymity. Your IP is only visible to you and the top admins and is not logged.\r\n[/color][/b]\r\njust follow the indication and you will be teleported automajically in our chat channel and you can talk to other users and the site admins and also get help with your problems. Notice the two options. One channel is for general chit-chat the other is for getting help.\r\n\r\n[b]Pay attention to the topic as it gives important information:[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-C026_5024677D.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\n\r\n[b]Few simple things you need to know.[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]1. Joining a channel[/b] \r\nWhen using the webchat (that is what we call it) to access the IRC, you can access other channels in addition as well. Say you joined the regular channel but also want to access the help one? Simply use the [b]/join[/b] command like below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-9F82_5024677D.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nand notice the new channel appearing in a new tab on top.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-AE4B_5024677D.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\n[b]2. The Status Window[/b]\r\nWhen you get in things may happen a bit fast for you to see or notice but there is a status window you can also access for useful information. Check it out by clicking the tab. \r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-348B_5022C067.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nWhen you click the tab you will see it:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-1B32_5022C139.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nOther than having a number of useful information, [color=#FF0000][b]and now [you] pay attention![/b][/color]\r\n\r\nIt is best to input commands in this window especially the ones involving your password. So if you mess up with a typo you can avoid that the whole channel sees your password.\r\n\r\nAlso some commands given in the channel show their result in the status window. So when you go WTF how come I do not see the result of my command, check the status window.\r\n\r\n[b]3. Private Chats[/b]\r\nYou can have private conversations with other users where only you two will see what is being said. But the etiquette requires you to ask first in the open channel if you do not know the user. You can do so by clicking on the user nick and selecting query.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-9942_502469C1.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\neach private conversation will be put in a separate tab. You can have many at the same time. And switch among them. If you receive a message while you are in another window, you will hear a sound and the tab will turn red to indicate activity.\r\n\r\n[b]4. Slap[/b]\r\nDo not be tempted by the slap command is not polite....  :laugh: \r\n\r\n[b]5. User categories[/b]\r\nIn the channels there are several user categories. \r\n\r\nFirst are the [b]IRC Staff[/b]. There is a hierarchy in our type of channel. ÃœberGods (~), Gods (&), Godlets (@) and Godlins(%). You do not have to worry about it. Just respect them and obey them. They are benevolent but do not attract their wrath with bad behavior. Play nice and they will be more than happy to help you if you need. In some channels they are arrogant assholes not in ours. Quite the contrary. \r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-2183_502545A9.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nThen there are [b]bots[/b]. These are not humans but programs that do useful things in the channel again no need to bother about them. Just know not to talk to them. Usually but not always they are indicated like [b]^botname^[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-878E_502546CD.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nThen the [b]voiced users[/b]. Voice is both functional and honorific. Function is to allow them to talk when the channel is put in moderated mode (rare for example in case of flame wars etc...). Honorific as it usually designate the regular contributing users. If you just idle you probably will not get voice. If you participate you will quickly get it. But you have to be registered. More on this later.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-3392_502548AF.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nAnd finally the other users. Maybe be new ones or just idlers.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-4200_50254CDE.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nHere is a more in depth explanation of the different user categories. According to the client used you may see them differently. From most to least powerful are:\r\n\r\n[img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-founder-symbol.png[/img][size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-founder-graphic.png[/img] - Founder - ultimate power. Can do anything to the channel and those within it. Usually represents the user who registered the channel. Only certain networks support founders.\r\n[img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-admin-symbol.png[/img][size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-admin-graphic.png[/img] - Admin - a normal operator, but protected from being kicked by anyone except the founder. Only certain networks support admins.\r\n[img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-op-symbol.png[/img][size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-op-graphic.png[/img] - Operator (op) - the user can grant and revoke operator, half-operator and voice status, change the topic, kick other users and generally control the channel.\r\n[img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-halfop-symbol.png[/img][size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-halfop-graphic.png[/img] - Half-operator (half-op) - the user has the power to moderate the channel, change the topic and kick people, but cannot kick other half-operators nor higher-ranking users, nor can he/she create new operators/half-operators. Only certain networks support half-operators.\r\n[img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-voice-symbol.png[/img][size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-voice-graphic.png[/img] - Voice - the user can talk in the channel when it is moderated. Often used to mark people as trusted or helpful without giving them any real power.\r\n[size=1]/[/size][img]http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/common/image/userlist-no-graphic.png[/img] - Normal - the user has no special status.\r\n\r\n\r\n[b]6. The /me command[/b]\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image-9D3E_50253E4D.jpg[/img]\r\n\r\nHow does he do it? Is a FAQ. Simply use the [b]/me[/b] command like [b]/me yawns[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]7. Register and Identify[/b]\r\n\r\nNow that you familiarized yourself with IRC and our channels you may want to register your nickname. \r\nYou may register your full site nickname up to 31 characters. Some other IRCs have shorter lengths we do not. We do require that you use the same one you use on the site.\r\n\r\nRegistering your nickname has several advantages like for example nobody other than you can use it so nobody can steal your identity. Because once you register your nickname, one will need a password to use it.\r\n\r\nYou will also be added to the auto-voice list so you get voiced automatically every time you enter.\r\n\r\n[color=#FF0000]Now [b]very important[/b] type these commands in the status window as well as all involving your password. So if you mess up you do not show your password in the channel for all to see!![/color]\r\n\r\nSo first make sure you are using the nickname you want. if not you can change it with:\r\n\r\n[b]/nick <nickname>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample : /nick barumba_is_the_man\r\n\r\nThen register your nickname:\r\n\r\n[b]/ns register <password> <email>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample: /ns register empircisfun barumba@gmail.com\r\n\r\nmake sure you use a password you remember!\r\nyou will not get an email notifications. This will only be used to recover your password. \r\nOnce given that command you are done. And you need to do it only once.\r\nIf you mess up contact the staff and they can help you fix it.\r\n\r\nOnce registered you need to announce yourself each time you enter [b]in the status window[/b] using:\r\n\r\n[b]/ns identify <password>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample: /ns identify empircisfun\r\n\r\nYou you can do it manually but with the new webchat interface you can have it done for you.\r\n\r\nFirst you select the channel(s) you want to join:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=3D8D_504BE626[/img]\r\n\r\nThen you select the Auth pull-down menu and input your password:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=4293_504BE3AA[/img]\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you decide to use one of the many IRC clients you can automate this. You can refer to the IRC clients chapter if you decide to use one.\r\n\r\nThis concludes this guide.\r\n\r\nCreated by [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/user.php?id=70679]Barumba[/url]. Minor edits by [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/user.php?id=85636]MrRandom[/url].','2012-09-10 19:52:35'),(68,1,4,'irc_clients',0,'02. IRC Clients for Dummies','Basic guide to IRC clients for our channels','[bg=grey,310px,left][color=white][font=Tahoma][size=4][align=center][b]Clients[/b][/align][/size][/font][/color]\r\n[bg=white,300px][bg=270px]\r\n[url=#webchat]Webchat[/url]\r\n[url=#mirc]mIRC[/url]\r\n[url=#chatzilla]ChatZilla[/url]\r\n[url=#xchat]xChat[/url]\r\n[url=#irssi]irssi[/url]\r\n[url=#limechat]LimeChat[/url]\r\n[url=#other]Other Clients[/url]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n\r\n[b][size=2]Ways to access our IRC Channels[/size][/b]\r\n\r\n[#=webchat][b]1. Using the Webchat[/b][/#] -> [color=#FF0000]not to state the obvious but.... you will make your life a LOT LOT LOT easier using a client instead.[/color]\r\n\r\nWith this option all you have to do is identify yourself in the [b]status window[/b]:\r\n\r\n[b]/ns identify <password>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample: /ns identify empircisfun\r\n\r\nthen use the [b]/join[/b] command in the [b]status window[/b] to join additional channels (this is a general IRC command and works with any client):\r\n\r\n/join #empornium-help\r\n\r\nyou can do this manually but with the new webchat interface you can have it done for you.\r\n\r\nFirst you select the channel(s) you want to join:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=3D8D_504BE626[/img]\r\n\r\nThen you select the Auth pull-down menu and input your password:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=4293_504BE3AA[/img]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=mirc][b]2. Using mIRC[/b][/#]\r\n\r\nmIRC is a fully fledged mature IRC client with tons of features. Worth mentioning is logging and scripting ability.\r\nIt is Windows only and is not for free.\r\n\r\nGetting mIRC.\r\n\r\nyou can use it for 30 days to see how you like it after that you need to register it and it is $20. Or.... well you know how to use torrents  :wink: \r\n\r\nyou can get mIRC here : [url=http://www.mirc.com/get.html]Download mIRC[/url]\r\n\r\nIf you are not familiar with mIRC after getting it and installing it read the guide (no point in duplicating it, is good) : [url=http://www.mirc.com/install.html]Link to first use guide[/url]\r\n\r\nThe add the empornium server like in the image below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=6AA4_50292650[/img]\r\n\r\nIn mIRC you can automate the identify. So you do not have to worry about it anymore.\r\n\r\nsimply go to [b]Tools [/b]then [b]Script Editor...[/b] and select the [b]Remote [/b]tab is is not.\r\n\r\nThen copy/paste this text in the window:\r\n\r\n[color=#0000FF]on 1:NOTICE:*This nickname is registered*:?: {\r\n  if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n    ns identify PASSWORD\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\non 1:NOTICE:*This nick is owned by someone else*:?: {\r\n  if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n    ns identify PASSWORD\r\n  }\r\n}[/color]\r\n\r\nand change the two instances of PASSWORD to yours. Click OK and you are done!\r\n\r\n[#=chatzilla][b]3. Using ChatZilla[/b] \r\n\r\nChatZilla is a Firefox plug-in so it works on any OS where Firefox can be installed. You install it like any other plug-in and access it from the tools window. \r\n\r\nGetting ChatZilla:\r\n\r\nTo get ChatZilla all you need is a Mozilla browser such as Firefox. First start up Firefox and then get ChatZilla from the add-on\'s site [b][u][url=https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/chatzilla/]here[/url].[/u][/b] \r\n\r\nyou may need to restart Firefox after you install ChatZilla.\r\n\r\n[img]http://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/chatzilla-install.png[/img]\r\n\r\nSetting up ChatZilla\r\n\r\nTo start ChatZilla click on tools, then ChatZilla. The ChatZilla client window will popup\r\n\r\n[img]http://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/chatzilla-fresh-installed.png[/img]\r\n\r\nto connect to Empornium IRC enter:\r\n\r\n[quote]/sslserver irc.emprn.tk 6697[/quote]\r\n\r\n[img]http://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/chatzilla-connect.png[/img]\r\n\r\nFor more information on ChatZilla [b][u][url=http://chatzilla.hacksrus.com/faq/#networks]please read this guide.[/url][/u][/b]\r\n\r\nWhen you connect you may be warned that the server has an invalid certificate, if so click \"add exeption\" and remember to change your nickname to the one you use on the site:\r\n\r\n[quote]/nick [you][/quote]\r\n\r\nFinally to join a channel simply enter:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #empornium[/quote]\r\n\r\n[img]http://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/chatzilla-in-channel.png[/img]\r\n\r\nThen use the /join command to join additional channels you want to use.\r\n\r\nYou can automate the identification in ChatZilla preferences see below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=7BE5_50292441[/img]\r\n\r\nand you can add channels for an auto-join when you start ChatZilla right click the channel tab and do as below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=87CD_50292441[/img]\r\n\r\n[#=xchat][b]4. XChat (thanks MrRandom for this)[/b][/#]\r\n\r\nHow to connect with xchat (this tutorial also works for clients based off of xchat such as HexChat)\r\n\r\nFirstly we need to get xchat installed. For linux users it should be in your repository e.g. ubuntu is \"sudo apt-get install xchat\". If you are on windows you can grab it from [url=http://www.silverex.org/download/]here[/url].\r\n\r\nWhen you first run xchat you will be presented with a server connect list.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xchat.org/docs/start/xchat-1-servlist.png[/img]\r\n\r\nChange your nickname and real name settings. Then click add to add a new IRC network and change the name to \"Empornium IRC\" and hit enter.\r\n\r\n[img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/xchat_server_edit.PNG[/img]\r\n\r\nClick edit double click on \"newserver/6667\" and change it to \"irc.digitalwizardry.org/6697\", [color=#FF0000]once edited click somewhere else or it will not be saved![/color] Click the check boxes on Use SSL and Accept invalid SSL Certificate, and if you registered your nickname enter the password you used.\r\n\r\n[img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/xchat_server_edit2.PNG[/img]\r\n\r\nClick the close button, then click connect and that\'s you you should be connected to Empornium IRC over secure SSL.\r\n\r\nIf you have any problems feel free to drop by #empornium-help.\r\n\r\n[#=irssi][b]5. IRSSI[/b][/#]\r\n\r\nLinux and Mac only but there is a windows version in beta.\r\n\r\nGetting Connected\r\n\r\nThe first step is to start irssi. Run from your shell:\r\n\r\n[quote]irssi[/quote]\r\n\r\nYou should now see irssi in its default stateâ€“disconnected, with some blue bars at the top and bottom.\r\n\r\nIn irssi, there are three important connection-related commands: /server, /connect, and /disconnect. irssi can handle multiple IRC connections simultaneously, thus it is possible to be active in channels on different networks at the same time. The first command, /server, will connect to the specified server on the current network. On the other hand, /connect will open a new network connection and connect to the specified server on the new network.\r\n\r\nFor example, typing /connect irc.foo.com will open a new network connection and connect to irc.foo.com. If you then type /connect irc.bar.com, there will be two network connections open, one for irc.foo.com, one for irc.bar.com. Typing /server irc.baz.com while the network connection for irc.bar.com is active will disconnect the client from irc.bar.com and connect to irc.baz.com on that network connection. You can use ctrl-X to switch between network connections. You can see what the active network is by looking at the status bar, which looks something like this:\r\n\r\n[align=center][img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/irssi_connect.PNG[/img][/align]\r\n\r\n(05:23:10) (irssi-test[+Tiwxz]) (1:SilentZombies (change with ^X))\r\n\r\nAt this point you should have a just-opened instance of irssi, with no connections to any server. Connect to an IRC server by typing:\r\n\r\n[quote]/connect -ssl irc.digitalwizardry.org 6697[/quote]\r\n\r\nand change your nickname with:\r\n\r\n[quote]/nick [you][/quote]\r\n\r\nIf everything connected fine, join a channel by typing:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #empornium[/quote]\r\n\r\n[align=center][img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/irssi_channel_join.PNG[/img][/align]\r\n\r\n[b]Switching Windows[/b]\r\n\r\nYou should now notice that the â€œstatusâ€ window is now hidden, and youâ€™re looking at the channel you just joined. You should also notice that your status bar says â€œ2:#emporniumâ€. This means that the window for #empornium is assigned window number 2. The status window is by default window number 1. To switch between windows in Irssi, use Alt-#, where # is 0-9. Windows start at number 1, and Alt-0 goes to window number 10. You can use Alt-q through Alt-o for windows 11 to 19. It is possible to have more than 19 windows. Use Alt with the arrow keys to scroll through the windows.\r\n\r\nTip: If youâ€™re trying to get to end windows past 19, start at window 1, and then use Alt with the left arrow key.\r\n\r\nAdvanced note: use /help bind to learn about the /bind command. It can be used to assign keyboard shortcuts to windows past 19.\r\n\r\nTo get support for auto-identifying you to nickserv you will need to get an external plugin for irssi:[url=http://scripts.irssi.org/scripts/nickserv.pl]http://scripts.irssi.org/scripts/nickserv.pl[/url]. Adding and managing plugins is beyond the scope of this tutorial but there are guides on how to do it on the IRSSI website.\r\n\r\n[#=limechat][b]6. LimeChat for iOS[/b][/#]\r\n\r\nYou can access our IRC channels from your iOS device.\r\n\r\nI used Limechat : [url=http://limechat.net/iphone/]LimeChat for iOS[/url]\r\n\r\nincidentally there is also a version for MacOS.\r\n\r\nYou just add your server and channel as you see below and configure and you are set....\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=EEF2_50292441[/img]\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=093D_5026B504[/img]\r\n\r\n[#=other][b]7. Using other clients[/b][/#]\r\n\r\nFor other clients I will incorporate any other anybody uses if you PM me the description and screens.','2012-10-23 03:36:06'),(69,1,3,'utorrent_config',0,'uTorrent configuration for Dummies','Advice on configuring uTorrent','Here is an example configuration. It is probably not perfect and can be improved upon but has worked for for quite some time. It is for version 3.1.2. To make this as easy as possible to follow below are screenshots of all settings panels. Above every screenshot is a small textual explanation.\r\n\r\nAt any time in uTorrent you can click the \"?\" in the blue circle up right for help on the panel options. If you see a reference to the \"I\" person that this would be one of our mods thanx to whom we have this overview.\r\n\r\n[b]General:[/b] Here is mostly up to you. Few things, I prefer it to start minimized.\r\nIMPORTANT : I found out that is a VERY good idea to check the the Pre-allocate option. This prevents the dreaded disk overload messages and loss of transfer speed as uTorrent keeps pre-allocating bits on the go.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap1.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]UI Settings: [/b] Again mostly up to your taste. I prefer for added torrent not to start automatically. This is particularly handy for uploads as it gives the opportunity to set the file location and do the force check before starting.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap2.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Directories: [/b] This way things stay nice and organized.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap3.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Connection: [/b] This the port uTorrent uses and that needs to be openend in your router in its NAT table (both TCP and UDP) for this there is a post already that explains how you are connectable. You can also use the Setup Guide to test that this is true.\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap4.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Bandwidth: [/b]This can be set running the wizard and tweaked later if you want to. You may want to limit rates if it is eating too much and you need to run other activities or if you have a crappy router that chokes after a while on fast connections. But best is to get a router that does not. Like a FritzBox. Zyxel are particularly bad in this respect.\r\n\r\nIf you are running under XP you may need to increase the connection numbers in the operating system. There are tools on line to do this. Windows 7 does not have this limitation.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap5.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]BitTorrent: [/b]Here you can set DHT etc... it does not matter and will work with sites that allow it and will be turned off automatically by private trackers that do not. Protocol Encryption up to you. I leave it disabled as if they want to catch you they do. But if you feel safer...\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap6.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Transfer Cap: [/b]I do not need it as have no cap on my connection but if you have one you may want to set it. And well see my usage... read and weep?\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap7.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Queueing: [/b]Again the Setup Guide can set this or you can and tweak. Depends from your speed. I set the Minimum Ratio to a high number so it will go until I decided to stop it or up to you again.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap8.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Scheduler: [/b]I do not use it. You may want to if you want to seed at higher speed etc during the night and so on.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap9.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Remote: [/b]With this setting you can have uTorrent create a website like gui for the client that you can access from anywhere in the world with an internet connection. This however requires several additional actions in terms of port forwarding and is not advisable to anyone that does not have atleast some profficiency with these matters.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap10.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Streaming: [/b]This feature allows you to make you own youtube. You can stream the videos and audio files you downloaded to an alternative location without having to download them.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap11.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]DNA: [/b]Special feature of uTorrent. Can be left off.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap12.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Advanced: [/b]As it says do not mess around until you know what you are doing. Explanation of each parameter in the help. I changed a few as you see in the screen to set the UI more to my liking (changed params are prefixed with an asterisk):\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap13.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap14.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap15.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]UI Extras: [/b]Did not change anything here. if you want then do it.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap16.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Disk Cache: [/b]These are my settings, I worked them out from info from different sources works for me. You may need a different setting.\r\nOK I looked at this again recently and here are some of my findings. If you do not have fast transfer speeds you may leave the cache management to uTorrent. If you have high transfer speeds and/or see the disk overloaded warning then you may play with this value up and down until you have the minimum amount to avoid the disk overloaded warning. Actually I recently found out that having this value too high like in the picture may be not a good idea as it can cause uTorrent to gobble too much memory and end up freezing or crashing.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap17.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap18.jpg[/IMG]\r\n\r\n[b]Web UI & Run Program: [/b]I do not use them. If you want then do.\r\n\r\n[IMG]http://i1261.photobucket.com/albums/ii581/barumba1/Snap19.jpg[/IMG]','2012-09-12 00:12:27'),(70,1,4,'irc_user',0,'08. IRC User commands','Describes the command availabe to users','[align=center][b][size=2]IRC User commands[/size][/b][/align]\r\n\r\n[b]Basic IRC Commands in alphabetical order[/b]\r\n\r\n[color=#00CC00][v] : works on our IRC server[/color]\r\n[color=#FF0000][x] : does not work on our IRC server[/color]\r\n\r\nJust as you are able to surf the net with a few tricks to help make things easier, IRC is very similar. Below you will find some of the more common IRC commands that generally work on any IRC channel. Some of these commands may be available through your client user interface like with right click.\r\n\r\n[b]/chat[/b] [color=#FF0000][x][/color]\r\n    This opens up a DCC/CHAT window to another user. What\'s nice about these is that you can continue to chat even if you \r\n    get disconnected from your server. \r\n    Word of Caution: Do NOT accept dcc/chats nor dcc/gets from anyone that you don\'t know. \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/chat nickname[/color]. \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/chat CyberAvatar[/color] \r\n\r\n[b]/help[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    There\'s one more very helpful command, and probably the one you\'ll use a lot when first starting out. In fact, I still\r\n    use it quite a lot, and that\'s the built-in help menu of your IRC client. \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/help[/color], you\'ll see the the options available specific to your IRC client.\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/help[/color] \r\n\r\n[b]/ignore[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Unfortunately, there will be times when you don\'t want to talk to someone, or else someone may be harassing you. \r\n    By typing [color=#FF0000]/ignore nickname[/color], you will not receive anymore messages from that person. \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/ignore annoyinguser[/color] \r\n    To Unignore them, type [color=#FF0000]/unignore annoyinguser[/color] \r\n    \r\n[b]/join[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/join #channelname[/color] -- to join a channel of your choice \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/join #empornium[/color]\r\n   \r\n[b]/me[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    The /me is an action message. \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/me \'does anything\'[/color] \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/me waves hello[/color] \r\n    \r\n[b]/msg[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/msg nickname (message)[/color] to start a private chat. \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/msg MrRandom Hey there, how are you?[/color] \r\n    Warning: IRC etiquette requires you to know the person or to ask first in the open channel.\r\n\r\n[b]/nick[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    changes your nickname \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/nick newnickname[/color]\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/nick barumba[/color](limit 9 characters in some systems up to 31 in ours) \r\n        \r\n[b]/notice[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    A notice is used to send a short message to another person without opening up a private window. \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/notice nickname (message)[/color] \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/notice clownius Please change your nickname for this channel.[/color] \r\n    \r\n[b]/part[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/part[/color] -- to leave one channel \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/partall[/color] -- to leave all the channels you are in\r\n\r\n[b]/ping[/b] [color=#FF0000][x][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/ping nickname[/color]. What this command does is give you the ping time, or lag time, between you and the person you \r\n    pinged. Lag can be explained as the amount of time it takes for you to type your message and for others to read your\r\n    messages. Unfortunately, lag is always a part of IRC, although most times it\'s not a problem, just a nuisance. \r\n\r\n[b]/query[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Similar to the /msg, except it forces a window to pop open and gives you a whois information.\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/query nickname (message)[/color] \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/query elkid Sooo....what\'s new?[/color] \r\n    Warning: same as /msg\r\n\r\n[b]/quit[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/quit [message][/color]to leave IRC altogether. This disconnects you from the server. Message is optional. I also clould close your client.\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/quit Going out for dinner...nite all[/color] \r\n    \r\n[b]/whois[/b] [color=#00CC00][v][/color]\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/whois nickname[/color] to see a bit more information about another user. You\'ll see what server another person is using, \r\n    or what their ISP is (on some systems, not ours the IP is masked for privacy purposes). Pretty helpful when you don\'t \r\n    recognize a nickname that wants to chat. You may recognize the IP, (Internet Protocol, again not shown in our system but\r\n    the owner and admins) and then feel more comfortable carrying on a conversation. You\'ll also be able to see what other \r\n    channels a person is in, which might be a good indicator if you really want to talk with them or not. \r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/whois mifune[/color]\r\n\r\n[color=#FF0000]*************** Below is work in progress, this warning will be removed once done ********[/color]    \r\n\r\n[b]Additional IRC Commands in alphabetical order[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]/admin[/b]\r\n    Provides Administrative information regarding the server.\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/admin[/color] \r\n\r\n[b]/away[/b]\r\n    Sets your online status to \"Away\". \r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/away reason[/color]\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/away lunchtime!\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/away[/color] to cancel away status\r\n\r\n[b]/dccallow <<+|->nick<,<+|->nick, ...>> <list> <help>[/b]\r\n    DCC is the file exchange system in IRC. You may allow DCCs of files which are otherwise blocked by the IRC server\r\n    by specifying a DCC allow for the user you want to recieve files from.\r\n    For instance, to allow the user Crozz to send you file.exe\r\n    Type [color=#FF0000]/dccallow +Crozz[/color]\r\n    and Crozz will then be able to send you files. Crozz will have to resend the file\r\n    if the server gave him an error message before you added him to your allow list.\r\n    [color=#FF0000]/dccallow -Crozz[/color]\r\n    Will do the exact opposite, removing him from your dcc allow list.\r\n    [color=#FF0000]/dccallow list[/color]\r\n    Will list the users currently on your dcc allow list.\r\n    [color=#FF0000]/dccallow help[/color]\r\n    will get you help on this command.\r\n\r\n[b]/invite <<user> <channel>>[/b]\r\n    Sends a user an Invitation to join a particular channel.\r\n    If the channel is +i (invisible), you must be an Operator to use this command, otherwise any user may use the command.\r\n    Invite without parameters lists the channels you have been invited to.\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/invite cocktail #empornium[/color]\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/invite[/color]\r\n\r\n[b]/ison <user1> <user2> <user3> <user4>[/b]\r\n    Used to determine if certain user(s) are currently online based upon their nickname.\r\n    Example: [color=#FF0000]/ison MrRandom Barumba Clownius Yamchan[/color]\r\n    \r\n\r\n','2012-08-26 20:43:04'),(71,2,4,'irc_halfop',0,'IRC Half Operator Commands','Describes the command availabe to half operators','','2012-08-16 21:30:02'),(72,2,4,'irc_op',0,'IRC Operator commands','Describes the command availabe to operators','','2012-08-16 21:29:17'),(73,2,4,'irc_admin',0,'IRC Adminstrator commands','Describes the command availabe to administrators','','2012-08-16 21:28:58'),(74,2,4,'irc_founder',0,'IRC Founder commands','Describes the command availabe to fouders','','2012-08-16 21:29:42'),(75,2,4,'irc_dump',0,'Dump article for all IRC stuff (DO NOT DELETE)','Used for moving things from the forum into a central repo.','============= NickServ Commands =============\r\n\r\nNickServ Commands\r\n\r\nNickServ allows you to â€œregisterâ€ a nickname and prevent others from using it. The following commands allow for registration and maintenance of nicknames; to use them, type /msg NickServ command. For more information on a specific command, type /msg NickServ HELP command.\r\n \r\n[b]REGISTER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ REGISTER password [email]\r\n \r\n Registers your nickname in the NickServ database.  Once\r\n your nick is registered, you can use the SET and ACCESS\r\n commands to configure your nick\'s settings as you like\r\n them.  Make sure you remember the password you use when\r\n registering - you\'ll need it to make changes to your nick\r\n later.  (Note that case matters!  ANOPE, Anope, and\r\n anope are all different passwords!)\r\n \r\n Guidelines on choosing passwords:\r\n \r\n Passwords should not be easily guessable.  For example,\r\n using your real name as a password is a bad idea.  Using\r\n your nickname as a password is a much worse idea ;) and,\r\n in fact, NickServ will not allow it.  Also, short\r\n passwords are vulnerable to trial-and-error searches, so\r\n you should choose a password at least 5 characters long.\r\n Finally, the space character cannot be used in passwords.\r\n \r\n The parameter email is optional and will set the email\r\n for your nick immediately. However, it may be required\r\n on certain networks.\r\n Your privacy is respected; this e-mail won\'t be given to\r\n any third-party person.\r\n \r\n This command also creates a new group for your nickname,\r\n that will allow you to register other nicks later sharing\r\n the same configuration, the same set of memos and the\r\n same channel privileges. For more information on this\r\n feature, type /msg NickServ HELP GROUP.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]GROUP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GROUP target password\r\n \r\n This command makes your nickname join the target nickname\'s\r\n group. password is the password of the target nickname.\r\n \r\n Joining a group will allow you to share your configuration,\r\n memos, and channel privileges with all the nicknames in the\r\n group, and much more!\r\n \r\n A group exists as long as it is useful. This means that even\r\n if a nick of the group is dropped, you won\'t lose the\r\n shared things described above, as long as there is at\r\n least one nick remaining in the group.\r\n \r\n You can use this command even if you have not registered\r\n your nick yet. If your nick is already registered, you\'ll\r\n need to identify yourself before using this command. Type\r\n /msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more information. This\r\n last may be not possible on your IRC network.\r\n \r\n It is recommended to use this command with a non-registered\r\n nick because it will be registered automatically when\r\n using this command. You may use it with a registered nick (to\r\n change your group) only if your network administrators allowed\r\n it.\r\n \r\n You can only be in one group at a time. Group merging is\r\n not possible.\r\n \r\n Note: all the nicknames of a group have the same password.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]IDENTIFY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  IDENTIFY password\r\n \r\n Tells NickServ that you are really the owner of this\r\n nick.  Many commands require you to authenticate yourself\r\n with this command before you use them.  The password\r\n should be the same one you sent with the REGISTER\r\n command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LOGOUT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LOGOUT\r\n \r\n This reverses the effect of the IDENTIFY command, i.e.\r\n make you not recognized as the real owner of the nick\r\n anymore. Note, however, that you won\'t be asked to reidentify\r\n yourself.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DROP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  DROP [nickname]\r\n \r\n Drops your nickname from the NickServ database.  A nick\r\n that has been dropped is free for anyone to re-register.\r\n \r\n You may drop a nick within your group by passing it\r\n as the nick parameter.\r\n \r\n In order to use this command, you must first identify\r\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\r\n information).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]ACCESS[b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ACCESS ADD mask\r\n         ACCESS DEL mask\r\n         ACCESS LIST\r\n \r\n Modifies or displays the access list for your nick.  This\r\n is the list of addresses which will be automatically\r\n recognized by NickServ as allowed to use the nick.  If\r\n you want to use the nick from a different address, you\r\n need to send an IDENTIFY command to make NickServ\r\n recognize you.\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     ACCESS ADD anyone@*.bepeg.com\r\n         Allows access to user anyone from any machine in\r\n         the bepeg.com domain.\r\n \r\n     ACCESS DEL anyone@*.bepeg.com\r\n         Reverses the previous command.\r\n \r\n     ACCESS LIST\r\n         Displays the current access list.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET option parameters\r\n \r\n Sets various nickname options.  option can be one of:\r\n \r\n     DISPLAY    Set the display of your group in Services\r\n     PASSWORD   Set your nickname password\r\n     LANGUAGE   Set the language Services will use when\r\n                    sending messages to you\r\n     URL        Associate a URL with your nickname\r\n     EMAIL      Associate an E-mail address with your nickname\r\n     ICQ        Associate an ICQ number with your nickname\r\n     GREET      Associate a greet message with your nickname\r\n     KILL       Turn protection on or off\r\n     SECURE     Turn nickname security on or off\r\n     PRIVATE    Prevent your nickname from appearing in a\r\n                    /msg NickServ LIST\r\n     HIDE       Hide certain pieces of nickname information\r\n     MSG        Change the communication method of Services\r\n     AUTOOP     Should services op you automatically.\r\n \r\n In order to use this command, you must first identify\r\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\r\n information).\r\n \r\n Type /msg NickServ HELP SET option for more information\r\n on a specific option.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET DISPLAY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET DISPLAY new-display\r\n \r\n Changes the display used to refer to your nickname group in\r\n Services. The new display MUST be a nick of your group.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET PASSWORD[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PASSWORD new-password\r\n \r\n Changes the password used to identify you as the nick\'s\r\n owner.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET URL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET URL url\r\n \r\n Associates the given URL with your nickname.  This URL\r\n will be displayed whenever someone requests information\r\n on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET EMAIL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET EMAIL address\r\n \r\n Associates the given E-mail address with your nickname.\r\n This address will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on the nickname with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET HIDE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET HIDE {EMAIL | STATUS | USERMASK | QUIT} {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Allows you to prevent certain pieces of information from\r\n being displayed when someone does a NickServ INFO on your\r\n nick.  You can hide your E-mail address (EMAIL), last seen\r\n user@host mask (USERMASK), your services access status\r\n (STATUS) and  last quit message (QUIT).\r\n The second parameter specifies whether the information should\r\n be displayed (OFF) or hidden (ON).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET ICQ[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET ICQ number\r\n \r\n Associates the given ICQ number with your nickname.  This\r\n number will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET GREET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET GREET message\r\n \r\n Makes the given message the greet of your nickname, that\r\n will be displayed when joining a channel that has GREET\r\n option enabled, provided that you have the necessary\r\n access on it.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET KILL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET KILL {ON | QUICK | IMMED | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns the automatic protection option for your nick\r\n on or off.  With protection on, if another user\r\n tries to take your nick, they will be given one minute to\r\n change to another nick, after which NickServ will forcibly change\r\n their nick.\r\n \r\n If you select QUICK, the user will be given only 20 seconds\r\n to change nicks instead of the usual 60.  If you select\r\n IMMED, user\'s nick will be changed immediately without being\r\n warned first or given a chance to change their nick; please\r\n do not use this option unless necessary.  Also, your\r\n network\'s administrators may have disabled this option.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET SECURE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET SECURE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns NickServ\'s security features on or off for your\r\n nick.  With SECURE set, you must enter your password\r\n before you will be recognized as the owner of the nick,\r\n regardless of whether your address is on the access\r\n list.  However, if you are on the access list, NickServ\r\n will not auto-kill you regardless of the setting of the\r\n KILL option.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET PRIVATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PRIVATE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns NickServ\'s privacy option on or off for your nick.\r\n With PRIVATE set, your nickname will not appear in\r\n nickname lists generated with NickServ\'s LIST command.\r\n (However, anyone who knows your nickname can still get\r\n information on it using the INFO command.)[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET MSG[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET MSG {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Allows you to choose the way Services are communicating with\r\n you. With MSG set, Services will use messages, else they\'ll\r\n use notices.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]UPDATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  UPDATE\r\n Updates your current status, i.e. it checks for new memos,\r\n sets needed chanmodes (ModeonID) and updates your vhost and\r\n your userflags (lastseentime, etc).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]RECOVER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RECOVER nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Allows you to recover your nickname if someone else has\r\n taken it; this does the same thing that NickServ does\r\n automatically if someone tries to use a kill-protected\r\n nick.\r\n \r\n When you give this command, NickServ will bring a fake\r\n user online with the same nickname as the user you\'re\r\n trying to recover your nick from.  This causes the IRC\r\n servers to disconnect the other user.  This fake user will\r\n remain online for NickServ to ensure that the other\r\n user does not immediately reconnect; after that time, you\r\n can reclaim your nick.  Alternatively, use the RELEASE\r\n command (/msg NickServ HELP RELEASE) to get the nick\r\n back sooner.\r\n \r\n In order to use the RECOVER command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]RELEASE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RELEASE nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Instructs NickServ to remove any hold on your nickname\r\n caused by automatic kill protection or use of the RECOVER\r\n command.  This holds lasts for NickServ;\r\n this command gets rid of them sooner.\r\n \r\n In order to use the RELEASE command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]GHOST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GHOST nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Terminates a \"ghost\" IRC session using your nick.  A\r\n \"ghost\" session is one which is not actually connected,\r\n but which the IRC server believes is still online for one\r\n reason or another.  Typically, this happens if your\r\n computer crashes or your Internet or modem connection\r\n goes down while you\'re on IRC.\r\n \r\n In order to use the GHOST command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]INFO[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  INFO nickname [ALL]\r\n \r\n Displays information about the given nickname, such as\r\n the nick\'s owner, last seen address and time, and nick\r\n options. If you are identified for the nick you\'re\r\n getting information for and ALL is specified, you will\r\n be shown all the information; regardless of whether\r\n it\'s hidden or not.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LIST pattern\r\n \r\n Lists all registered nicknames which match the given\r\n pattern, in nick!user@host format.  Nicks with the\r\n PRIVATE option set will not be displayed.\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     LIST *!joeuser@foo.com\r\n         Lists all nicks owned by joeuser@foo.com.\r\n \r\n     LIST *Bot*!*@*\r\n         Lists all registered nicks with Bot in their\r\n         names (case insensitive).\r\n \r\n     LIST *!*@*.bar.org\r\n         Lists all nicks owned by users in the bar.org\r\n         domain.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]ALIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ALIST [level]\r\n \r\n Lists all channels you have access on. Optionally, you can specify\r\n a level in XOP or ACCESS format. The resulting list will only\r\n include channels where you have the given level of access.\r\n\r\n Examples:\r\n     ALIST Founder\r\n         Lists all channels where you have Founder\r\n         access.\r\n\r\n     ALIST AOP\r\n         Lists all channels where you have AOP\r\n         access or greater.\r\n\r\n     ALIST 10\r\n         Lists all channels where you have level 10\r\n         access or greater.\r\n\r\n Channels that have the NOEXPIRE option set will be\r\n prefixed by an exclamation mark.[/quote]\r\n[b]GLIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GLIST\r\n \r\n Lists all nicks in your group.[/quote]\r\n[b]STATUS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  STATUS nickname...\r\n \r\n Returns whether the user using the given nickname is\r\n recognized as the owner of the nickname.  The response has\r\n this format:\r\n \r\n     nickname status-code\r\n \r\n where nickname is the nickname sent with the command, and\r\n status-code is one of the following:\r\n \r\n     0 - no such user online or nickname not registered\r\n     1 - user not recognized as nickname\'s owner\r\n     2 - user recognized as owner via access list only\r\n     3 - user recognized as owner via password identification\r\n \r\n Up to sixteen nicknames may be sent with each command; the\r\n rest will be ignored. If no nickname is given, your status\r\n will be returned.[/quote]\r\n \r\n ============= Registration Nickname =============\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRegistering your nickname on Empornium IRC provides a number of benefits. The most notable of these is that registering your nickname prevents other people from using it. Once a user starts using the nickname, they will be asked to â€˜identifyâ€™ to it with a password. If they fail to do so, their nickname will be changed. This helps to stop people posing as you.\r\n\r\nOnce you register your nickname, you can be added to the auto voice and op lists in other peopleâ€™s channels. This enables you to be a permanent staff member in channels. You are also entitled to a vhost once you have been registered.\r\n\r\nRegistration provides you with many benefits and is completely free.\r\n\r\nTo register your nickname on Empornium IRC, you must first be using it. If you are not currently using it, change to it with the command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/nick <nickname>[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n[quote]/nick CrazyUser[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you are using the nickname, you may register it in one of two ways. In any client, use the following command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register <password> <e-mail>[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register supersecretpassword crazyuser@hotmail.com[/quote]\r\n\r\nFollowing this, you will be sent an e-mail giving you the details required to finish off the registration. Follow the instructions in the e-mail.\r\n\r\nEach time you connect and start using the registered, you will be told that â€œThis nick is owned by someone elseâ€. You must â€˜identifyâ€™ to it using the following command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns identify <password>[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns identify supersecretpassword[/quote]\r\n\r\nIf you use mIRC, you can load the following script into the Remotes section of your script editor (press alt+R to access this) to identify you automatically. Just replace â€˜YOURPASSWORDHEREâ€™ with your actual password:\r\n\r\non 1:NOTICE:*This nickname is registered and protected*:?: {\r\n   if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n      ns identify YOURPASSWORDHERE\r\n   }\r\n}\r\n\r\non 1:NOTICE:*This nick is owned by someone else*:?: {\r\n   if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n      ns identify YOURPASSWORDHERE\r\n   }\r\n}\r\n\r\nIf you require help, come and see us in [url=http://torrents.empornium.me/irc.php]#empornium-help on irc.emprn.tk[/url]. Users who have registered with NickServ will automatically get voiced in the channel when they join.\r\n\r\n============= Registration Channel =============\r\n\r\nRegistering your channel on Empornium IRC gives you many advantages, and is completely free. These include:\r\n\r\nIncreased control over your channel\r\nAbility to add people to the auto op list\r\nAbility to add auto kicks\r\nAbility to use a services bot to auto moderate your channel\r\nAnd many many moreâ€¦\r\nTo register your channel, you must first register your nickname. To do this, when you are using the nickname that you wish to register, type the following command into your IRC client:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register password e-mail[/quote]\r\n\r\nYou must replace password and e-mail with a real password and e-mail address, respectively. An example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register supersecretpassword fred@hotmail.com[/quote]\r\n\r\nIt is important that you use your real e-mail address as this will be used in future if you ever forget your password. We will not send any unsolicited e-mail to this address.\r\n\r\nOnce you have registered your nickname, you can register your channel. All channels names begin with the # symbol, for example #help, #chris and #247fixes. Once you have picked a channel name, you can join it using the command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #channel[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #chat[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you have joined the channel, if it is not already registered, you should see your name in the nickname list with the @ symbol next to it. This means you are an operator in the channel. You may now register it with the following command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/cs register #channel password description[/quote]\r\n\r\nYou must replace #channel, password and description with the channel name, the channel password and a description of the channel. An example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/cs register #chat verysecretpassword Freds chat channel[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you have done that, you should see your name in the nick list prefixed with the ~ symbol. This means you are the owner of the channel.\r\n\r\nIf you have any problems registering your channel, come and talk to us in #help on irc.emprn.tk\r\n\r\n============= Extended Bans =============\r\n\r\n[b]Silencing Users with Extended Bans[/b]\r\nYou can use extended bans to set up an alternative kind of ban that will give you more options, like silencing users.\r\n\r\nWhen you silence a user, you allow the person to stay in the channel, but block the personâ€™s ability to participate in the discussion or change nicks. Itâ€™s an online equivalent of a short timeout, where the person has to sit quietly for several minutes before rejoining discussion.\r\n\r\nTo silence a user manually, youâ€™d type:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +bb ~q:nick!ident@user.host ~n:nick!ident@user.host[/quote]\r\nThat command sets two bans, which is why the host information is listed twice. The first one (~q:nick!ident@user.host) prevents the user from participating in the discussion (unless the user is +v or higher). The ~q stands for quiet. The second one (~n: nick!ident user.host) prevents the user from changing nicks. The ~n stands for nick.\r\n\r\nIn #YourChannel, bans are normally set by the userâ€™s host, so an example ban would look like this:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +bb ~n:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net ~q:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net[/quote]\r\nThat example bans anyone (with any nick or ident) with the hostmask protectedhost-12345678.hsd1.va.comcast.net.\r\n\r\n \r\n[b]Removing a Silence Extended Ban[/b]\r\nIf you silence a user manually, you have to remove the ban manually as well. Since you set the ban with +b, you will remove it by using the same command, but with -b. So to remove the ban, you would type:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -bb ~q:nick!ident@user.host ~n:nick!ident@user.host[/quote]\r\nEverything is the same. Youâ€™re just removing the ban. Hereâ€™s the way to remove the example ban from above:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -bb ~n:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net ~q:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]Setting a Channel Extended Ban[/b]\r\nThere are two other kinds of extended bans:\r\n\r\n~c sets an extended ban based on a channel users are in\r\n~r sets an extended ban based on a userâ€™s real name\r\nYou are unlikely to need either of these bans, but for the sake of thoroughness here is how they work.\r\n\r\nTo set an extended channel ban, youâ€™d type:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~c:#channel[/quote]\r\nThat ban would prevent anyone in #channel from joining #YourChannel.\r\n\r\nLetâ€™s pretend thereâ€™s a channel called #YourChannelHaters. We might decide that we do not want anyone from #YourChannelHaters to join #YourChannel. We could use this extended ban to prevent them from joining #YourChannel:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~c:#YourChannelHaters[/quote]\r\nYou remove this kind of ban by switching to -b, so I could remove the ban on folks from #YourChannelHaters like this:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -b ~c:#YourChannelHaters[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]Setting a Real Name Extended Ban[/b]\r\nTo set an extended ban based on a userâ€™s real name, youâ€™d type:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~r:*real_name*[/quote]\r\nThe * character works as a wildcard, just as it does in other bans. Use the underscore character ( _ ) to represent spaces in the userâ€™s real name. The underscore is also interpreted as an actual underscore character. In other words, the ban above would block someone using either â€œreal nameâ€ (with a space) or â€œreal_nameâ€ (with an underscore).\r\n\r\nHereâ€™s an example: \r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~r:*Jane_Doe*[/quote]\r\nThat ban would prevent anyone who was using the real name â€œJane Doeâ€ or â€œJane_Doeâ€ from joining #YourChannel. Because of the * wildcard, someone with a real name like â€œJane Doe rulesâ€ or â€œJane_Doe_rulesâ€ would also be banned.\r\n\r\nYou remove this kind of ban by switching to -b, so I could remove the ban on â€œJane Doe â€ like this:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -b ~r:*Jane_Doe*[/quote]\r\n\r\n============= Make A Channel Private =============\r\n\r\nAt least twice a month, someone will come into #help asking about private channels or how they can secure their channel to prevent anyone except those they want in it. Since there are probably those that would like to know, but donâ€™t ask, here is the quick and dirty guide to private/secret channels.\r\n\r\nEvery channel is able to be either private (+p), or secret (+s). The two modes are similar, but it is possible for people to find out about a channel that is marked private (+p). Therefore, if you want a channel nobody will be able to find out about unless theyâ€™re told, it is recommended that you mark it as secret, +s. Unless you are in the channel or an IRCop, the server will pretend that the channel doesnâ€™t exist.\r\n\r\nThere is also channel mode +i, which will let people in only when they have been invited. If the channel is registered with chanserv, those on the access list can /msg chanserv invite #channel, and chanserv (or the botserv bot, if the channel has one) will invite the person into the channel. Standing invites can also be set using channel mode +I, which takes a nick!ident@host mask as a parameter. If the person is not on the access list, and does not have +I set for themselves, they are able to â€œknockâ€ on the channel by doing /knock #channel optional_message.\r\n\r\nYou can also set a â€œkeyâ€ on the channel using channel mode +k, which takes the key to use as a parameter. If I wanted to set a key on my channel, I would do /mode #serenity +k Kaylee. In order to get in the channel, someone would need to specify the key when they try to join â€“ /join #serenity Kaylee. Alternatively, they can also be invited into the channel and will not need the key.\r\n\r\nIf the channel is registered, those modes can be mlockâ€™ed, so that they will be reapplied when the channel is recreated (i.e. is empty and someone joins). It is important to note that if the channel is empty, needing a key or an invite is not necessary to join the channel. That is where the next item comes into play.\r\n\r\nIt is also possible to set a channel to have restricted access. When this option is set, only the people you add to the access list will be able to join. When someone that is not on the list attempts to join, they are kickbanned by chanserv (or the botserv bot, if you have added one) with the reason â€œYou are not permitted to be on this channelâ€.\r\n\r\nSince when you set your channel to restricted access you normally donâ€™t want people to know about it, it is recommended to also mlock it +s. To set both the restricted access and mlock, you need to enter the following two commands, replacing #channel with your actual channel:\r\n[quote]/msg chanserv set #channel mlock +s[/quote]\r\n[quote]/msg chanserv set #channel restricted on[/quote]\r\nNote: If you already have some modes set with mlock, you will need to respecify them when you add +s. So if you have +n (no external messages) set with mlock, you would need to do /msg chanserv set #channel mlock +sn.\r\n\r\nShould you have any questions concerning setting your channel to restricted access, feel free to stop in #help and ask.\r\n\r\n============= Grouping Nicks =============\r\n\r\nSo youâ€™ve registered your nick, but have more than one computer/device that you join IRC from. You might be wondering â€œdo I need to register a new nick and have people add that nick to access lists as well? Certainly there must be an easier way.â€\r\n\r\nWell luckily for you, there is. You are able to group nicks together so that permissions and other data are shared among accounts. Some of the items that are shared include (but are not limited to): channel ownership, permission levels (owner, halfop, etc.) on channels, group info that was provided when you registered, password, and virtual host. Pretty much anything your single nick has associated with it will be associated with the group of nicks that you have registered.\r\n\r\nHereâ€™s how to group a nick to one that you already have registered:\r\nSwitch to the nick that you want to group\r\nNOTE 1: Before you enter the next command, make sure that you are using the nick you want to add to your existing group. Do NOT be using your main nick. Example: if I wanted to group JayneCobb to my account, I would /nick JayneCobb.\r\nNOTE 2: If you use a registered nick when the next step if performed, it will first be dropped, then grouped to the main nick. Example: if I try to group JayneCobb (which is registered) to my main nick MalcolmReynolds, Services will first drop JayneCobb, then have it join the MalcolmReynolds group. By being dropped, any permissions JayneCobb had will be gone.\r\nEnter the following command in the server/status window: /msg nickserv group main_nick password, where main_nick is your primary nick, and password is the password belonging to the primary nick.\r\nExample: I want to group JayneCobb to my primary nick, MalcolmReynolds, and the password for it is S3reni+yV@ll3y (you do use something secure for your passwords, right?). I would type the following as JayneCobb: /msg nickserv group MalcolmReynolds S3reni+yV@ll3y\r\nLook for nickserv to either tell you that you have joined the group of your primay nick or give you an error message, such as â€œyou must wait at least 60 seconds before using the group command againâ€.\r\nAnd just to give you the commands again, they are, in order:\r\n[quote]/nick theNewNick[/quote]\r\n[quote]/msg nickserv group main_nick password[/quote]\r\n\r\nNow what if you want to delink a nick, i.e. remove it from the group, is there some way to do that? Yes there is, you just drop it by switching to the nick, and doing /msg nickserv drop. Doing that will make nickserv completely drop the nick â€“ it will no longer exist, have any permissions, etc.\r\n\r\nIs there someway to delink it without dropping, or without it losing the permissions and other information? Not currently, although I suppose it is possible that it could end up in a future version of anope, or someone could create a module that could drop a nick and register it using the credentials of the former group and preserving permissions, etc.\r\n\r\nShould you have any questions about grouping nicks, feel free to leave a comment here, or to join #help and ask in there.\r\n\r\n\r\n=========== Flood Protection ===========\r\n\r\nThe +f channel mode provides comprehensive flood protection for a channel. This mode allows you to prevent join, nick change, CTCP, text, and knock floods. The syntax for this modeâ€™s parameter is as follows:\r\n\r\n/mode #channel +f [{#}{,...}]:\r\n\r\nThe amount specifies the number of times the specified flood must occur before action is taken. Below are the available types:\r\n\r\nType	Name	Default Actions	Other Actions\r\nc	CTCP	+C (no channel CTCPs allowed)	m (only voiced users can speak), M (only registered users can speak)\r\nj	Join	+i (invite only)	R (only registered users can join)\r\nk	Knock	+K (no knocks allowed)	 \r\nm	Messages	+m (only voiced users can speak)	+M (only registered users can speak)\r\nn	Nickname Change	+N (no nickname changes allowed)	 \r\nt	Text	User is kicked from the channel	+b (user is banned from the channel)\r\nThe difference between type m and t is that m is tallied for the entire channel whereas t is tallied per user.\r\n\r\nIf you choose to specify an action for a mode, you may also specify a time (in minutes) after which the specific action will be reversed.\r\n\r\nAn example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n/mode #chills +f [2c#C5,6j#R3,3k#K10,15m#m5,5n#N3,5t#b60]:5\r\n\r\nThis meansâ€¦\r\n\r\nIf there are 2 channel CTCP messages (2c) in 5 seconds(:5) set mode +C for 5 mins (#C5)\r\nIf there are 6 joins (6j) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +R for 3 mins (#R3)\r\nIf there are 3 /KNOCK commands on the channel (3k) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +K for 10 mins (#K10)\r\nIf there are 15 messages in total from all users (15m) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +m for 5 mins (#m5)\r\nIf there are 5 nickname changes (n5) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +N for 3 mins (#N3)\r\nIf there are 5 messages from any single user (5t) in 5 seconds (:5) ban the user for 60 mins (#b60)\r\nIt has been observed lately that bot nets are joining channels and rapidly joining and parting. In order to prevent this, you can use channel mode j. This mode will allow only x joins to your channel in y seconds for each client. The recommended setting for this is 1 join in 1 second as this will entirely eradicate join/part flooding from botnets. An example of the use of this is:\r\n\r\n/mode #chills +j 1:1\r\n\r\nIf you need any help, come and see us in #help on irc.geekshed.net\r\n\r\n============= Fantasy/Bot Commands =============\r\n\r\nFantasy commands allows you to use simple shortcuts in place of many of the NickServ, ChanServ, and BotServ commands. \r\n\r\nThe available commands are listed below; to use them, just type the command indicated (for instance, For more information on a specific command, type !help command.) \r\n\r\nThe Fantasy commands are arranged in xxx areas:\r\nGeneral Commands â€“ General commands available. No special access required.\r\nAccess Control Commands â€“ Commands to manipulate channel access and levels list(s).\r\nChannel Settings Commands â€“ Commands to configure the channelsâ€™ settings and lists.\r\nChannel Action Commands â€“ Commands that will make services perform certain actions.\r\nChannel Modes Commands â€“ Commands that set certain channel modes.\r\n\r\nUsing Fantasy Commands\r\nTo use Fantasy commands, you first have to turn on the option, using this command:\r\n/msg botserv set #channel fantasy on\r\nFor instance, if I wanted to turn on Fantasy commands in #topgear, Iâ€™d use this command:\r\n/bs set #topgear fantasy on\r\nOnce Fantasy commands are turned on, you can use any of the commands below, as long as you have the proper access. In other words, you cannot kick someone if youâ€™re not a hop or op on the channel.\r\n\r\n[u][b]General Commands[/b][/u]\r\n \r\n!HELP\r\n Syntax: !HELP\r\n \r\n Help for BotServ fantasy commands\r\n \r\n!CMDLIST\r\n Syntax: !CMDLIST\r\n \r\n  A list of all available fantasy commands\r\n \r\n!IRCOPS\r\n Syntax: !IRCOPS\r\n \r\n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window\r\n \r\n!STAFF\r\n Syntax: !STAFF\r\n \r\n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window\r\n \r\n!MINFO\r\n Syntax: !MINFO\r\n \r\n Shows information about the module providing the brunt \r\n of the fantasy commands.\r\n \r\n!SVERSION\r\n Syntax: !SVERSION\r\n \r\n Shows information about the Anope IRC Services version \r\n and build.\r\n \r\n!INFO\r\n Syntax: !INFO [ALL]\r\n \r\n  Shows information about the channel. \r\n The \'all\' option is limited to founders and Services Admins.\r\n \r\n[u][b]Access Control Commands[/b][/u]\r\n\r\n!SOP\r\n Syntax: !SOP add nick\r\n         !SOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !SOP list [mask | list]\r\n         !SOP clear\r\n \r\n Maintains the SOP (SuperOP) list for the channel.\r\n The SOP list gives users all rights given by the AOP list, and adds\r\n those needed to use the AutoKick and the BadWords lists,\r\n to send and read channel memos, and so on.\r\n  \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\r\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\r\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\r\n \r\n!AOP\r\n Syntax: !AOP add nick\r\n         !AOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !AOP list [mask | list]\r\n         !AOP clear\r\n \r\n Maintains the AOP (AutoOP) list for the channel.\r\n The AOP list gives users the right to be auto-opped on your channel,\r\n to unban or invite themselves if needed, to have their\r\n greet message showed on join, and so on.\r\n  \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\r\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\r\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\r\n \r\n!HOP\r\n Syntax: !HOP add nick\r\n         !HOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !HOP list [mask | list]\r\n         !HOP clear\r\n \r\n Maintains the HOP (HalfOP) list for the channel. The HOP\r\n list gives users the right to be auto-halfopped on your channel\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\r\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\r\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\r\n \r\n Provides access to the HOP (HalfOP) list.\r\n \r\n!VOP\r\n Syntax: !VOP add nick\r\n         !VOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !VOP list [mask | list]\r\n         !VOP clear\r\n \r\n Maintains the VOP (VOicePeople) list for a channel.\r\n The VOP list allows users to be auto-voiced and to voice\r\n themselves if they aren\'t.\r\n  \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\r\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\r\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\r\n \r\n!ACCESS\r\n Syntax: !ACCESS add nick level\r\n         !ACCESS del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !ACCESS list [mask | list]\r\n         !ACCESS clear\r\n \r\n Maintains the access list for a channel.  The access\r\n list specifies which users are allowed chanop status or\r\n access to commands on the channel.\r\n \r\n Different user levels allow for access to different subsets of\r\n privileges; cf. /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more specific \r\n information. Any nick not on the access list has a user level of 0.\r\n \r\n!LEVELS\r\n Syntax: !LEVELS set type level\r\n         !LEVELS {dis | disable} type\r\n         !LEVELS list\r\n         !LEVELS reset\r\n \r\n The LEVELS command allows fine control over the meaning of\r\n the numeric access levels used for the channel.  With this command,\r\n you can define the access level required for most administrative functions.\r\n (The SET FOUNDER and SET PASSWORD commands, as well as this command, \r\n are always restricted to the channel founder.) \r\n \r\n LEVELS SET allows the access level for a function or group of \r\n functions to be changed.\r\n \r\n LEVELS DISABLE (or DIS for short) disables an automatic\r\n feature or disallows access to a function by anyone other \r\n than the channel founder.\r\n \r\n LEVELS LIST shows the current levels for each function or group\r\n  of functions.\r\n \r\n LEVELS RESET resets the levels to the default levels of a \r\n newly-created channel.\r\n \r\n (See /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more info.)\r\n \r\n For a list of the features and functions whose levels can be\r\n set, see HELP LEVELS DESC.\r\n \r\n[b][u]Channel Setting Commands[/b][/u]\r\n\r\n!AKICK\r\n Syntax: !AKICK add {mask | user} [reason]\r\n         !AKICK {stick | unstick | del} mask\r\n         !AKICK {list | view} [mask]\r\n         !AKICK {enforce | clear}\r\n \r\n Maintains the channel AKICK list. See the ChanServ AKICK command for more details.\r\n \r\n!BADWORDS\r\n Syntax: !BADWORDS add word [single | start | end | any]\r\n         !BADWORDS del {word | entry-num | list}\r\n         !BADWORDS list [mask | list]\r\n         !BADWORDS clear\r\n \r\n  Maintains the badwords list. See the  BotServ BADWORDS command  for more details.\r\n \r\n!SET\r\n Syntax: !SET option parameters\r\n \r\n Changes channel\'s settings. \r\n   \r\n Available options:\r\n See the ChanServ SET command for more details on the following:\r\n   founder       -  Set the founder of a channel\r\n   successor     -  Set the successor for a channel\r\n   desc          -  Set the channel description\r\n   url           -  Associate a URL with the channel\r\n   email         -  Associate an E-mail address with the channel\r\n   entrymsg      -  Set a message to be sent to users when they enter the \r\n                    channel\r\n   bantype       -  Set how Services make bans on the channel\r\n   mlock         -  Lock channel modes on or off\r\n   keeptopic     -  Retain topic when channel is not in use\r\n   topiclock     -  Topic can only be changed with TOPIC\r\n   opnotice      -  Send a notice when OP/DEOP commands are used\r\n   peace         -  Regulate the use of critical commands\r\n   private       -  Hide channel from LIST command\r\n   restricted    -  restrict access to the channel\r\n   secure        -  activate services\' security features\r\n   secureops     -  stricter control of chanop status\r\n   securefounder -  stricter control of channel founder status\r\n   signkick      -  Sign kicks that are done with KICK command\r\n   xop           -  Toggle the user privilege system\r\n \r\n \r\n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following:\r\n   noexpire      -  Sets whether the given channel will expire. \r\n                    (limited to SA)\r\n   dontkickops   -  Protect channel ops against kicks by the services bot.\r\n   dontkickvoices - Protect voices against kicks by the services bot.\r\n   greet         -  Enable greet messages on join.\r\n   fantasy       -  Enable fantasy commands on the channel.\r\n   symbiosis     -  Allow the bot to act as a real bot.\r\n   nobot         -  Prevents a bot from being assigned to this channel. \r\n                    (limited to SA)\r\n    \r\n!BKICK\r\n Syntax: !BKICK option {on | off} [ttb [params]]\r\n \r\n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following options:\r\n \r\n   bolds       -  Sets whether the bot kicks bolds.\r\n   badwords    -  Sets whether the bots kicks for words in  \r\n                  the badwords list.\r\n   caps        -  Sets whether the bot kicks for CAPS.\r\n   colors      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for colors.\r\n   flood       -  Sets whether the bot kicks for floods.\r\n   repeat      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for repeats.\r\n   reverses    -  Sets whether the bot kicks for reverses.\r\n   underlines  -  Sets whether the bot kicks for underlines.\r\n  \r\n ttb is the number of times a user can be kicked before he gets banned.\r\n Don\'t give ttb to disable the ban system once activated.\r\n\r\n[u][b]Channel Action Commands[/u][/b]\r\n\r\n!CLEAR\r\n Syntax: !CLEAR {modes | bans | excepts | invites | ops | hops | voices | users}\r\n \r\n Clears the specified option on the channel. \r\n See the ChanServ CLEAR command for more details.\r\n \r\n!TOPIC\r\n Syntax: !TOPIC [topic]\r\n         !CTOPIC\r\n Sets the channel topic. If no topic is given, the current \r\n topic is displayed in the channel.\r\n \r\n The CTOPIC command clears the topic.\r\n \r\n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK \r\n \r\n See the ChanServ TOPIC command for more details.\r\n \r\n!TAPPEND\r\n Syntax: {!TAPPEND  | !APPENDTOPIC}  text to be appended to topic\r\n \r\n Appends the given text to the channel\'s current topic.\r\n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK \r\n \r\n!INVITE\r\n Syntax: !INVITE\r\n \r\n  Invites \'nick\' to the channel if the user is present on the network.\r\n \r\n!UP\r\n Syntax: !UP\r\n \r\n Gives the user the modes he has rights to. This will unset modes if he has any\r\n the user has no access to.\r\n \r\n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \r\n a Services Root Administrator.\r\n \r\n!DOWN\r\n Syntax: !DOWN [nick] [level]\r\n \r\n Unsets all modes. If the channel is moderated, it will reset voice,\r\n unless issued on another user by a founder. It is also possible\r\n to specify a target level. \r\n\r\n The target level can be any one of the following:\r\n \r\n    - q - Channel founder (modes +qo) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - a - Protected Operator / Administrator (modes +ao) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - o - Channel Operator (mode +o)\r\n    - h - Channel Halfop (mode +h) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - v - \\\"Voice\\\" (mode +v)\r\n \r\n If a target level is specified, the users\' current privileges will be  \r\n replaced by the target one.\r\n  \r\n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \r\n a Services Root Administrator.\r\n \r\n!KICK\r\n Syntax: !KICK [nick [reason]]\r\n \r\n Kick a user from the channel.\r\n See the ChanServ KICK command for more details.\r\n \r\n!KB\r\n Syntax: {!KICKBAN | !KB} [nick!]ident@host] [reason]\r\n \r\n This will kick and ban the specified user or all users matching the given \r\n mask from the channel. If a mask is given and someone who should not be \r\n kicked according to the channels\' settings matches it, the command is \r\n aborted before anyone is kicked or banned.\r\n \r\n!TKB\r\n Syntax: !tkb or !tkban [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time] [reason]\r\n \r\n This will kick and temporarily ban the specified user or all users matching\r\n the given mask from the channel for the specified amount of time. \r\n \r\n If a mask is given and someone who should not be banned according to the\r\n channels\' settings matches it, the command is aborted before anyone is \r\n kicked.\r\n \r\n Also be aware that this command may not work with IPs for privacy reasons.\r\n\r\n If the time is not given or is invalid, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n \r\n Example: !tkb SillyTroll 10m Bye \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n \r\n Note: if Services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\r\n not be automatically removed.\r\n \r\n[b][u]Channel Modes Commands[/b][/u]\r\n\r\n!BAN\r\n Syntax: !BAN [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Bans (a) user(s)/mask from the channel without kicking.\r\n \r\n!TBAN\r\n Syntax: {!TB | !TBAN} [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time]\r\n \r\n This will ban the given nick or hostmask from the channel for the specified\r\n amount of time. If the time is not given, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n \r\n Example: !tb SillyTroll 10m \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n \r\n Note: if services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\r\n not be automatically removed\r\n!UNBAN\r\n Syntax: !UNBAN [nick | [nick!]ident@host]\r\n \r\n  Removes the ban on a user.\r\n \r\n!MUTE\r\n Syntax: !MUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Bans or mutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n \r\n!UNMUTE\r\n Syntax: !UNMUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Unbans or unmutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n \r\n!OP\r\n Syntax: !OP  [nick]\r\n \r\n Op yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ  OP command \r\n for more details.\r\n \r\n!DEOP\r\n Syntax: !DEOP  [nick]\r\n \r\n Deop yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ OP command \r\n for more details.\r\n \r\n!VOICE\r\n Syntax: !VOICE [nick]\r\n \r\n Voice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ VOICE command \r\n for more details.\r\n \r\n!DEVOICE\r\n Syntax: !DEVOICE [nick]\r\n \r\n Devoice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEVOICE command \r\n for more details.\r\n \r\n!PROTECT\r\n Syntax: !PROTECT [nick]\r\n \r\n Protect yourself or another user (so you cannot be kicked). See \r\n the ChanServ PROTECT command for more details.\r\n \r\n!DEPROTECT\r\n Syntax: !DEPROTECT [nick]\r\n \r\n Remove protection from  yourself or another user. See the \r\n ChanServ DEPROTECT command for more details.\r\n \r\n!OWNER\r\n Syntax: !OWNER\r\n \r\n Give yourself the owner mode. See the ChanServ OWNER command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n \r\n!DEOWNER\r\n Syntax: !DEOWNER\r\n \r\n Remove the owner mode. See the ChanServ DEOWNER command for \r\n more details.\r\n \r\n!HALFOP\r\n Syntax: !HALFOP [nick]\r\n \r\n Halfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ HALFOP command \r\n for more details.\r\n \r\n!DEHALFOP\r\n Syntax: !DEHALFOP [nick]\r\n \r\n Dehalfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEHALFOP command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n============= IRC Operator Commands =============\r\n\r\n[b]OPER[/b]\r\n Syntax: /OPER userid password\r\n \r\n Command to give a user operator status if they match an\r\n Oper Block\r\n \r\n[b]WALLOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /WALLOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all users with umode +w\r\n \r\n[b]GLOBOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GLOBOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all global IRCops\r\n \r\n[b]CHATOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHATOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all IRCops (local and global)\r\n \r\n[b]LOCOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /LOCOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all local IRCops\r\n \r\n[b]ADCHAT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADCHAT message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all Admins\r\n \r\n[b]NACHAT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /NACHAT message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all Net Admins\r\n \r\n[b]KILL[/b]\r\n Syntax: /KILL nick reason\r\n \r\n Kills a user from the network\r\n \r\n[b]KLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /KLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Bans the hostmask from the server it is issued on. A\r\n kline is not a global ban.   time to ban is\r\n either: a) a value in seconds, b) a time value, like\r\n \'1d\' is 1 day or c) \'0\' for permanent.  Time and reason\r\n are optional, if unspecified set::default-bantime\r\n (default: 0/permanent) and \'no reason\' are used.  To\r\n remove a kline use /kline -user@host\r\n \r\n[b]ZLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Bans an IP Address from the local server it is issued\r\n on (not global). See kline for more syntax info.   Use\r\n /zline -*@ip to remove.\r\n \r\n[b]GLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Adds a global ban to anyone that matches. See kline for\r\n more syntax info.      Use /gline -user@host to remove.\r\n \r\n[b]SHUN[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SHUN [+|-]user@host | nick [time to shun reason]\r\n \r\n Prevents a user from executing ANY commands and\r\n prevents them from speaking. Shuns are global (like\r\n glines). See kline for more syntax info. Use /shun\r\n -user@host to remove a shun.\r\n \r\n[b]GZLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GZLINE [+|-]ip time to ban :reason\r\n \r\n Adds a global zline. See kline for more syntax info.\r\n   Use /gzline -*@ip to remove a gzline.\r\n \r\n[b]REHASH[/b]\r\n Syntax: /REHASH server â€“flags\r\n \r\n Rehashes the servers config file. Including a server\r\n name allows you to rehash a remote servers config file.\r\n Several flags are also available. They Include -motd -\r\n Only rehash all MOTD and RULES files (including tld {})\r\n      -opermotd - Only rehash the OPERMOTD file\r\n -botmotd - Only rehash the BOTMOTD file      -garbage -\r\n Force garbage collection\r\n\r\n[b]SETHOST[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SETHOST newhost\r\n \r\n Lets you change your vhost to what ever you want it to\r\n be.\r\n \r\n[b]SETIDENT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SETIDENT newident\r\n \r\n Lets you set your ident to what ever you want it to be\r\n \r\n[b]CHGHOST[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGHOST nick newhost\r\n \r\n Lets you change the host name of a user currently on\r\n the system\r\n \r\n[b]CHGIDENT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGIDENT nick newident\r\n \r\n Lets you change the ident of a user currently on the\r\n system\r\n \r\n[b]CHGNAME[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGNAME nick newname\r\n \r\n Lets you change the realname of a user currently on the\r\n system\r\n \r\n[b]SQUIT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SQUIT server\r\n \r\n Disconnects a server from the network\r\n DO NOT USE UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT YOU\'RE DOING\r\n \r\n[b]CONNECT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CONNECT server port server\r\n \r\n If only one server is given, it will attempt to connect\r\n the server you are ON to the given server. If 2 servers\r\n are given, it will attempt to connect the 2 servers\r\n together. Put the leaf server as the first, and the hub\r\n server as the second.\r\n \r\n[b]DCCDENY[/b]\r\n Syntax: /DCCDENY filemask reason\r\n \r\n Adds a DCCDENY for that filemask. Preventing that file\r\n from being sent.\r\n \r\n[b]UNDCCDENY[/b]\r\n Syntax: /UNDCCDENY filemask\r\n \r\n Removes a DCCDENY\r\n \r\n[b]RPING[/b]\r\n Syntax: /RPING servermask\r\n \r\n Will calculate in milliseconds the lag between servers\r\n \r\n[b]TRACE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /TRACE servermask|nickname\r\n \r\n When used on a user it will give you class and lag\r\n info. If you use  it on a server it gives you\r\n class/version/link info.\r\n \r\n[b]OPERMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /OPERMOTD\r\n \r\n Displays the servers OperMotd File\r\n \r\n[b]ADDMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADDMOTD :text\r\n \r\n Will add the given text to the end of the Motd\r\n \r\n[b]ADDOMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADDOMOTD :text\r\n \r\n Will add the given text to the end of the OperMotd\r\n \r\n[b]SDESC[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SDESC newdescription\r\n \r\n Allows server admins to change the description line of\r\n their server without restarting.\r\n  \r\n[b]CLOSE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CLOSE\r\n \r\n This command will disconnect all unknown connections\r\n from the IRC server.\r\n \r\n============= ChanServ Commands =============\r\n\r\nChanServ allows you to register and control various aspects of channels. ChanServ can often prevent malicious users from â€œtaking overâ€ channels by limiting who is allowed channel operator privileges. Available commands are listed below; to use them, type /msg ChanServ command. For more information on a specific command, type /msg ChanServ HELP command.\r\n \r\n[b]REGISTER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  REGISTER channel password description\r\n \r\n Registers a channel in the ChanServ database.  In order\r\n to use this command, you must first be a channel operator\r\n on the channel you\'re trying to register.  The password\r\n is used with the IDENTIFY command to allow others to\r\n make changes to the channel settings at a later time.\r\n The last parameter, which must be included, is a\r\n general description of the channel\'s purpose.\r\n \r\n When you register a channel, you are recorded as the\r\n \"founder\" of the channel.  The channel founder is allowed\r\n to change all of the channel settings for the channel;\r\n ChanServ will also automatically give the founder\r\n channel-operator privileges when s/he enters the channel.\r\n See the ACCESS command (/msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS) for\r\n information on giving a subset of these privileges to\r\n other channel users.\r\n \r\n NOTICE: In order to register a channel, you must have\r\n first registered your nickname.  If you haven\'t,\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP for information on how to do so.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]IDENTIFY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  IDENTIFY channel password\r\n \r\n Authenticates you to ChanServ as the founder of the given\r\n channel.  Many commands require you to use this command\r\n before using them.  The password should be the same one\r\n you sent with the REGISTER command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LOGOUT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  LOGOUT channel nickname\r\n \r\n This command will log the selected nickname out meaning they\r\n would have to reidentify themselves to regain their access.\r\n \r\n If you are the founder of the channel, you can log out anybody,\r\n else you can only log out yourself.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DROP[/b]\r\n[/quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ DROP channel\r\n \r\n Unregisters the named channel.  Can only be used by\r\n channel founder, who must use the IDENTIFY command first.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel option parameters\r\n \r\n Allows the channel founder to set various channel options\r\n and other information.\r\n \r\n Available options:\r\n \r\n     FOUNDER       Set the founder of a channel\r\n     SUCCESSOR     Set the successor for a channel\r\n     PASSWORD      Set the founder password\r\n     DESC          Set the channel description\r\n     URL           Associate a URL with the channel\r\n     EMAIL         Associate an E-mail address with the channel\r\n     ENTRYMSG      Set a message to be sent to users when they\r\n                      enter the channel\r\n     BANTYPE       Set how Services make bans on the channel\r\n     MLOCK         Lock channel modes on or off\r\n     KEEPTOPIC     Retain topic when channel is not in use\r\n     OPNOTICE      Send a notice when OP/DEOP commands are used\r\n     PEACE         Regulate the use of critical commands\r\n     PRIVATE       Hide channel from LIST command\r\n     RESTRICTED    Restrict access to the channel\r\n     SECURE        Activate ChanServ security features\r\n     SECUREOPS     Stricter control of chanop status\r\n     SECUREFOUNDER Stricter control of channel founder status\r\n     SIGNKICK      Sign kicks that are done with KICK command\r\n     TOPICLOCK     Topic can only be changed with TOPIC\r\n     XOP           Toggle the user privilege system\r\n \r\n Type /msg ChanServ HELP SET option for more information on a\r\n particular option.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET FOUNDER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel FOUNDER nick\r\n \r\n Changes the founder of a channel.  The new nickname must\r\n be a registered one.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SUCCESSOR[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SUCCESSOR nick\r\n \r\n Changes the successor of a channel.  If the founder\'s\r\n nickname expires or is dropped while the channel is still\r\n registered, the successor will become the new founder of the\r\n channel.  However, if the successor already has too many\r\n channels registered (<num>), the channel will be dropped\r\n instead, just as if no successor had been set.  The new\r\n nickname must be a registered one.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET PASSWORD[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PASSWORD password\r\n \r\n Sets the password used to identify as the founder of the\r\n channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET DESC[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel DESC description\r\n \r\n Sets the description for the channel, which shows up with\r\n the LIST and INFO commands.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET URL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel URL [url]\r\n \r\n Associates the given URL with the channel.  This URL will\r\n be displayed whenever someone requests information on the\r\n channel with the INFO command.  If no parameter is given,\r\n deletes any current URL for the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET EMAIL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel EMAIL [address]\r\n \r\n Associates the given E-mail address with the channel.\r\n This address will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on the channel with the INFO command.  If no\r\n parameter is given, deletes any current E-mail address for\r\n the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET ENTRYMSG[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel ENTRYMSG [message]\r\n \r\n Sets the message which will be sent via /notice to users\r\n when they enter the channel.  If no parameter is given,\r\n causes no message to be sent upon entering the channel.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET BANTYPE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel BANTYPE bantype\r\n \r\n Sets the ban type that will be used by services whenever\r\n they need to ban someone from your channel.\r\n \r\n bantype is a number between 0 and 3 that means:\r\n \r\n 0: ban in the form *!user@host\r\n 1: ban in the form *!*user@host\r\n 2: ban in the form *!*@host\r\n 3: ban in the form *!*user@*.domain[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET KEEPTOPIC[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel KEEPTOPIC {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the topic retention option for a\r\n channel.  When topic retention is set, the topic for the\r\n channel will be remembered by ChanServ even after the\r\n last user leaves the channel, and will be restored the\r\n next time the channel is created.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET TOPICLOCK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel TOPICLOCK {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the topic lock option for a channel.\r\n When topic lock is set, ChanServ will not allow the\r\n channel topic to be changed except via the TOPIC\r\n command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET MLOCK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel MLOCK modes\r\n \r\n Sets the mode-lock parameter for the channel. ChanServ\r\n allows you to define certain channel modes to be always\r\n on, off or free to be either on or off.\r\n \r\n The modes parameter is constructed exactly the same way\r\n as a /MODE command; that is, modes followed by a + are\r\n locked on, and modes followed by a - are locked off. Note,\r\n however, that unlike the /MODE command, each use of\r\n SET MLOCK will remove all modes previously locked before\r\n setting the new!\r\n \r\n Warning:  If you set a mode-locked key, as in the second\r\n example below, you should also set the RESTRICTED option for\r\n the channel (see HELP SET RESTRICTED), or anyone entering\r\n the channel when it is empty will be able to see the key!\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +nt-iklps\r\n         Forces modes n and t on, and modes i, k, l, p, and\r\n         s off.  Mode m is left free to be either on or off.\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +knst-ilmp my-key\r\n         Forces modes k, n, s, and t on, and modes i, l, m,\r\n         and p off.  Also forces the channel key to be\r\n         \"my-key\".\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +\r\n         Removes the mode lock; all channel modes are free\r\n         to be either on or off.\r\n		 [/quote]\r\n[b]SET PEACE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PEACE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the peace option for a channel.\r\n When peace is set, an user won\'t be able to kick,\r\n ban or remove a channel status of an user that has\r\n a level superior or equal to his via ChanServ commands.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET PRIVATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PRIVATE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the private option for a channel.\r\n When private is set, a /msg ChanServ LIST will not\r\n include the channel in any lists.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET RESTRICTED[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel RESTRICTED {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the restricted access option for a\r\n channel.  When restricted access is set, users not on\r\n the access list will instead be kicked and banned from the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECURE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECURE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables ChanServ\'s security features for a\r\n channel.  When SECURE is set, only users who have\r\n registered their nicknames with ChanServ and IDENTIFY\'d\r\n with their password will be given access to the channel\r\n as controlled by the access list.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECUREOPS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECUREOPS {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the secure ops option for a channel.\r\n When secure ops is set, users who are not on the userlist\r\n will not be allowed chanop status.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECUREFOUNDER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECUREFOUNDER {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the secure founder option for a channel.\r\n When secure founder is set, only the real founder will be\r\n able to drop the channel, change its password, its founder and its\r\n successor, and not those who are IDENTIFY\'d with ChanServ.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SIGNKICK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SIGNKICK {ON | LEVEL | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables signed kicks for a\r\n channel.  When SIGNKICK is set, kicks issued with\r\n ChanServ KICK command will have the nick that used the\r\n command in their reason.\r\n \r\n If you use LEVEL, those who have a level that is superior\r\n or equal to the SIGNKICK level on the channel won\'t have their\r\n kicks signed. See /msg ChanServ HELP LEVELS for more information.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET XOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel XOP {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the xOP lists system for a channel.\r\n When XOP is set, you have to use the AOP/SOP/VOP\r\n commands in order to give channel privileges to\r\n users, else you have to use the ACCESS command.\r\n \r\n Technical Note: when you switch from access list to xOP\r\n lists system, your level definitions and user levels will be\r\n changed, so you won\'t find the same values if you\r\n switch back to access system!\r\n \r\n You should also check that your users are in the good xOP\r\n list after the switch from access to xOP lists, because the\r\n guess is not always perfect... in fact, it is not recommended\r\n to use the xOP lists if you changed level definitions with\r\n the LEVELS command.\r\n \r\n Switching from xOP lists system to access list system\r\n causes no problem though.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET OPNOTICE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel OPNOTICE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the op-notice option for a channel.\r\n When op-notice is set, ChanServ will send a notice to the\r\n channel whenever the OP or DEOP commands are used for a user\r\n in the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]AOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  AOP channel ADD nick\r\n         AOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         AOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         AOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the AOP (AutoOP) list for a channel. The AOP\r\n list gives users the right to be auto-opped on your channel,\r\n to unban or invite themselves if needed, to have their\r\n greet message showed on join, and so on.\r\n \r\n The AOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n AOP list.\r\n \r\n The AOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n AOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The AOP LIST command displays the AOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    AOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists AOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The AOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n AOP list.\r\n \r\n The AOP ADD and AOP DEL commands are limited to\r\n SOPs or above, while the AOP CLEAR command can only\r\n be used by the channel founder. However, any user on the\r\n AOP list may use the AOP LIST command.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]HOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  HOP channel ADD nick\r\n         HOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         HOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         HOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the HOP (HalfOP) list for a channel. The HOP\r\n list gives users the right to be auto-halfopped on your\r\n channel.\r\n \r\n The HOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n HOP list.\r\n \r\n The HOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n HOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The HOP LIST command displays the HOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    HOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists HOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The HOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n HOP list.\r\n \r\n The HOP ADD, HOP DEL and HOP LIST commands are\r\n limited to AOPs or above, while the HOP CLEAR command\r\n can only be used by the channel founder.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SOP channel ADD nick\r\n         SOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         SOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         SOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the SOP (SuperOP) list for a channel. The SOP\r\n list gives users all rights given by the AOP list, and adds\r\n those needed to use the AutoKick and the BadWords lists,\r\n to send and read channel memos, and so on.\r\n \r\n The SOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n SOP list.\r\n \r\n The SOP DEL comma','2012-08-17 21:11:29'),(76,1,4,'irc_staff_power',0,'07. What staff can and cannot do on IRC.','Clearing up the myths about what staff can and cannot do.','[align=center][b][size=2]What staff can and cannot do on IRC[/size][/b][/align]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nQ: What can ALL staff (halfops and above) do? \r\nA: This is a list of what ALL of us can do:\r\n\r\nBan a user from the channel.\r\nkick a user from the channel\r\nMass msg/CTCP/notice a channel we have op\'s in.\r\nGive voice to any user\r\nChange the topic of the channel\r\n\r\nQ: What can MOST staff (ops and above) do? \r\nA: In addition to the above, this is a list of what MOST staff can do:\r\n\r\nOp other users in the channel.\r\nAdd ban exemptions for any hostmask.\r\nChange almost any channel mode.\r\nGet custom channel greet messages.\r\n\r\nQ: What can SOME staff (admins and above) do? \r\nA: In addition to the above, this is a list of what SOME staff can do:\r\n\r\nAdd users to the autovoice, auto halfop and auto op list\'s.\r\nMake ^empornium^ talk.\r\nAdd autokicks for almost any hostmask.\r\n\r\nQ: What can 3 of the staff (IRC Operators) do?\r\nA: In addition to the above, this is a list of what 3 staff can do:\r\n\r\nView your IP address.\r\nBan you from the their server.\r\nBan you from the network.\r\nSuspend your nickserv account.\r\nChange your vHost.\r\n\r\nQ: With all of this power, what can staff NOT do?\r\nA: staff can NOT:\r\n\r\nTrack nickname changes on clients that are not in a channel in common with them.\r\nOp ourselves in a channel, unless we have the right access in services.\r\nOp anyone else in a channel, unless we have ops.\r\nDe-op someone in a channel, unless we have ops.\r\nView any private messages you send to other people.\r\nView chat in any channel we are not in.','2012-09-10 18:19:15'),(77,2,1,'creditsinline',0,'inline credits explanation ','used on the bonus shop page','\r\n[#=what]What is a credit?[/#]\r\n\r\nCredits are distributed as a bonus to people who are seeding torrents. You can find your total credit amount at the top of this page, or on your user details page.\r\n\r\n[#=what]How is the credit calculated?[/#]\r\n\r\nThe amount of credits you earn per hour depends on how many torrents you are seeding. More torrents means more credits but when you are seeding more than 20 torrents per hour the extra amount per torrent is slightly less.\r\n\r\n[spoiler=Amount of credits per hour][color=black]\r\n[font=Courier New]\r\n[table][tr]\r\n[td]\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| torrents | credits |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| 1        | 2       |\r\n| 2        | 3       |\r\n| 3        | 5       |\r\n| 4        | 6       |\r\n| 5        | 7       |\r\n| 6        | 8       |\r\n| 7        | 9       |\r\n| 8        | 10      |\r\n| 9        | 11      |\r\n| 10       | 12      |\r\n| 11       | 13      |\r\n| 12       | 14      |\r\n| 13       | 15      |\r\n| 14       | 16      |\r\n| 15       | 16      |\r\n| 16       | 17      |\r\n| 17       | 18      |\r\n| 18       | 19      |\r\n| 19       | 19      |\r\n| 20       | 20      |\r\n| 21       | 21      |\r\n| 22       | 21      |\r\n| 23       | 22      |\r\n| 24       | 23      |\r\n| 26       | 24      |\r\n| 28       | 25      |\r\n| 30       | 26      |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n[/td][td]  \r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| torrents | credits |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| 35       | 29      |\r\n| 40       | 31      |\r\n| 45       | 34      |\r\n| 50       | 36      |\r\n| 55       | 38      |\r\n| 60       | 40      |\r\n| 65       | 42      |\r\n| 70       | 44      |\r\n| 80       | 47      |\r\n| 85       | 49      |\r\n| 90       | 51      |\r\n| 95       | 52      |\r\n| 100      | 54      |\r\n| 110      | 57      |\r\n| 120      | 60      |\r\n| 130      | 63      |\r\n| 140      | 65      |\r\n| 150      | 68      |\r\n| 160      | 71      |\r\n| 170      | 73      |\r\n| 180      | 75      |\r\n| 200      | 80      |\r\n| 220      | 84      |\r\n| 240      | 88      |\r\n| 260      | 92      |\r\n| 280      | 96      |\r\n| 300      | 100     |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n[/td][td]  \r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| torrents | credits |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n| 350      | 109     |\r\n| 400      | 117     |\r\n| 450      | 125     |\r\n| 500      | 132     |\r\n| 550      | 139     |\r\n| 600      | 145     |\r\n| 650      | 152     |\r\n| 700      | 158     |\r\n| 750      | 163     |\r\n| 800      | 169     |\r\n| 850      | 175     |\r\n| 900      | 180     |\r\n| 1000     | 190     |\r\n| 1200     | 209     |\r\n| 1400     | 227     |\r\n| 1600     | 243     |\r\n| 1800     | 259     |\r\n| 2000     | 273     |\r\n| 2200     | 287     |\r\n| 2400     | 300     |\r\n| 2600     | 313     |\r\n| 2800     | 325     |\r\n| 3000     | 337     |\r\n| 5000     | 437     |\r\n| 10000    | 623     |\r\n| 15000    | 765     |\r\n| 20000    | 884     |\r\n+----------+---------+\r\n[/td]\r\n[/tr][/table]\r\n[/font][/color][/spoiler]\r\n\r\n\r\nThe maths is: \r\nROUND( ( SQRT( 8.0 * ( COUNT( * ) /20 ) + 1.0 ) - 1.0 ) / 2.0 *20 )  per hour\r\nwhere COUNT( * ) = the total number of torrents you are seeding.\r\n','2012-08-31 22:57:19'),(78,1,6,'shop',0,'Bonus Shop','A place to spend your credits','\r\n\r\n<< insert guide here >>','2012-09-03 18:02:08'),(79,1,5,'winscreenshots',0,'How to create screenshots (Windows)','Step by step guide into making screenshots on windows','[center][color=#0261a3][size=5][font=Arial Black]How to create screenshots (Windows)[/font][/size][/color][/center]\r\n\r\nThis tutorial will guide you to make sequential thumbnails or screenshots of a video file. Sequential thumbnail means it will automatically take screenshots from a video after some interval and scale them to a smaller size. Our result will have a single image page containing several thumbnails or screenshots from a video. A great thing if you are sharing a video. People always wants to see what is in a video before they download it.\r\n\r\nFirst we need to install a free software (open source) called Media Player Classic (you probably have it anyway). If not\r\n\r\nDownload:\r\n\r\n[url]http://prdownloads.sourceforge.net/guliverkli/mpc2kxp6490.zip?download[/url]\r\n[url]http://sourceforge.net/projects/guliverkli/files/Media%20Player%20Classic/MPC%206.4.9.0/mpc98me6490.zip/download[/url]\r\n\r\nThe software doesn\'t even need any installation. Simply extract the .zip and run the mplayerc.exe\r\n\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=C71B_4EA7043D][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=C71B_4EA7043D[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nThis brings up the Media Player Classic.\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=0E5A_4EA707F8][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=0E5A_4EA707F8[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nNow lets open our video file. Click on File > Quick Open Fileâ€¦\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=A070_4EA7090D][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=A070_4EA7090D[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nBrowse to the file and open it.\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=098E_4EA707F8][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=098E_4EA707F8[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nNow click on File > Save Thumbnailsâ€¦\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=D33C_4EA70B5F][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=D33C_4EA70B5F[/img][/url]\r\n\r\n\r\nThis brings up the Save As dialogue box.\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=BC5E_4EA70CAF][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=BC5E_4EA70CAF[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nNote the thumbnail settings. This determines the size of the thumbnail page and how many thumbnails will be generated.\r\n\r\nThe above setting shows there will be 4 columns and 4 rows of thumbnails totalling (4Ã—4=) 16 thumbnails. And the thumbnail page width will be 1024 pixels.\r\n\r\nNow lets change the setting to have 6 rows and 5 columns of thumbnails totalling (6Ã—5=) 30 thumbnails. Also setting the thumbnail page to be of width 600 pixels.\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=6FEA_4EA707F8][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=6FEA_4EA707F8[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nThe image should be saved as JPEG (.jpg) to reduce the file size. \r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=B07C_4EA70D4D][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=B07C_4EA70D4D[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nClick on the Save button to save it.\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=3524_4EA707F8][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=3524_4EA707F8[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nAnd we have our thumbnails\r\n[url=http://xxx.freeimage.us/share.php?id=DFA4_4EA707F8][img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/thumb.php?id=DFA4_4EA707F8[/img][/url]\r\n\r\nWhen you have created your screens upload them to [url]http://xxx.freeimage.us/[/url] then add the \"BBcode for forum\" link to your presentation.\r\n\r\nNOTE: if your file is too big then change the number of images or the pixel size to something smaller and try again (this will depend on how many images in the screens and the file size)\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------\r\n\r\nor you can use a free app called thumbnailme\r\n[url]http://anonym.to/http://www.thumbnailme.com[/url]\r\n\r\nthere is sort of guide how to use it here [url]http://torrents.empornium.me/forums.php?action=viewtopic&topicid=103[/url]\r\n\r\n\r\nPlease do not PM me for more support as I cannot give one to one for all members - please use the help & support forum here :\r\n[url]http://torrents.empornium.me/forums.php?action=viewforum&forumid=6[/url]','2012-09-07 15:44:18'),(80,1,5,'linscreenshots',0,'How to create screenshots (Linux)','Step by step guide into making screenshots on linux','[center][color=#0261a3][size=5][font=Arial Black]How to create screenshots (Linux)[/font][/size][/color][/center]\r\n\r\nPlaceholder: Need to combine several forum posts into 1 article. Will edit this.','2012-09-07 15:49:10'),(81,1,4,'irc_nickserv',0,'10. NickServ Commands','In depth description of NickServ Commands','[align=center][b][size=2]NickServ Commands[/size][/b][/align]\r\n\r\nNickServ allows you to â€œregisterâ€ a nickname and prevent others from using it. The following commands allow for registration and maintenance of nicknames; to use them, type /msg NickServ command. For more information on a specific command, type /msg NickServ HELP command.\r\n \r\n[b]REGISTER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ REGISTER password [email]\r\n \r\n Registers your nickname in the NickServ database.  Once\r\n your nick is registered, you can use the SET and ACCESS\r\n commands to configure your nick\'s settings as you like\r\n them.  Make sure you remember the password you use when\r\n registering - you\'ll need it to make changes to your nick\r\n later.  (Note that case matters!  ANOPE, Anope, and\r\n anope are all different passwords!)\r\n \r\n Guidelines on choosing passwords:\r\n \r\n Passwords should not be easily guessable.  For example,\r\n using your real name as a password is a bad idea.  Using\r\n your nickname as a password is a much worse idea ;) and,\r\n in fact, NickServ will not allow it.  Also, short\r\n passwords are vulnerable to trial-and-error searches, so\r\n you should choose a password at least 5 characters long.\r\n Finally, the space character cannot be used in passwords.\r\n \r\n The parameter email is optional and will set the email\r\n for your nick immediately. However, it may be required\r\n on certain networks.\r\n Your privacy is respected; this e-mail won\'t be given to\r\n any third-party person.\r\n \r\n This command also creates a new group for your nickname,\r\n that will allow you to register other nicks later sharing\r\n the same configuration, the same set of memos and the\r\n same channel privileges. For more information on this\r\n feature, type /msg NickServ HELP GROUP.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]GROUP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GROUP target password\r\n \r\n This command makes your nickname join the target nickname\'s\r\n group. password is the password of the target nickname.\r\n \r\n Joining a group will allow you to share your configuration,\r\n memos, and channel privileges with all the nicknames in the\r\n group, and much more!\r\n \r\n A group exists as long as it is useful. This means that even\r\n if a nick of the group is dropped, you won\'t lose the\r\n shared things described above, as long as there is at\r\n least one nick remaining in the group.\r\n \r\n You can use this command even if you have not registered\r\n your nick yet. If your nick is already registered, you\'ll\r\n need to identify yourself before using this command. Type\r\n /msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more information. This\r\n last may be not possible on your IRC network.\r\n \r\n It is recommended to use this command with a non-registered\r\n nick because it will be registered automatically when\r\n using this command. You may use it with a registered nick (to\r\n change your group) only if your network administrators allowed\r\n it.\r\n \r\n You can only be in one group at a time. Group merging is\r\n not possible.\r\n \r\n Note: all the nicknames of a group have the same password.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]IDENTIFY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  IDENTIFY password\r\n \r\n Tells NickServ that you are really the owner of this\r\n nick.  Many commands require you to authenticate yourself\r\n with this command before you use them.  The password\r\n should be the same one you sent with the REGISTER\r\n command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LOGOUT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LOGOUT\r\n \r\n This reverses the effect of the IDENTIFY command, i.e.\r\n make you not recognized as the real owner of the nick\r\n anymore. Note, however, that you won\'t be asked to reidentify\r\n yourself.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DROP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  DROP [nickname]\r\n \r\n Drops your nickname from the NickServ database.  A nick\r\n that has been dropped is free for anyone to re-register.\r\n \r\n You may drop a nick within your group by passing it\r\n as the nick parameter.\r\n \r\n In order to use this command, you must first identify\r\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\r\n information).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]ACCESS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ACCESS ADD mask\r\n         ACCESS DEL mask\r\n         ACCESS LIST\r\n \r\n Modifies or displays the access list for your nick.  This\r\n is the list of addresses which will be automatically\r\n recognized by NickServ as allowed to use the nick.  If\r\n you want to use the nick from a different address, you\r\n need to send an IDENTIFY command to make NickServ\r\n recognize you.\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     ACCESS ADD anyone@*.bepeg.com\r\n         Allows access to user anyone from any machine in\r\n         the bepeg.com domain.\r\n \r\n     ACCESS DEL anyone@*.bepeg.com\r\n         Reverses the previous command.\r\n \r\n     ACCESS LIST\r\n         Displays the current access list.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET option parameters\r\n \r\n Sets various nickname options.  option can be one of:\r\n \r\n     DISPLAY    Set the display of your group in Services\r\n     PASSWORD   Set your nickname password\r\n     LANGUAGE   Set the language Services will use when\r\n                    sending messages to you\r\n     URL        Associate a URL with your nickname\r\n     EMAIL      Associate an E-mail address with your nickname\r\n     ICQ        Associate an ICQ number with your nickname\r\n     GREET      Associate a greet message with your nickname\r\n     KILL       Turn protection on or off\r\n     SECURE     Turn nickname security on or off\r\n     PRIVATE    Prevent your nickname from appearing in a\r\n                    /msg NickServ LIST\r\n     HIDE       Hide certain pieces of nickname information\r\n     MSG        Change the communication method of Services\r\n     AUTOOP     Should services op you automatically.\r\n \r\n In order to use this command, you must first identify\r\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\r\n information).\r\n \r\n Type /msg NickServ HELP SET option for more information\r\n on a specific option.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET DISPLAY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET DISPLAY new-display\r\n \r\n Changes the display used to refer to your nickname group in\r\n Services. The new display MUST be a nick of your group.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET PASSWORD[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PASSWORD new-password\r\n \r\n Changes the password used to identify you as the nick\'s\r\n owner.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET URL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET URL url\r\n \r\n Associates the given URL with your nickname.  This URL\r\n will be displayed whenever someone requests information\r\n on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET EMAIL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET EMAIL address\r\n \r\n Associates the given E-mail address with your nickname.\r\n This address will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on the nickname with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET HIDE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET HIDE {EMAIL | STATUS | USERMASK | QUIT} {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Allows you to prevent certain pieces of information from\r\n being displayed when someone does a NickServ INFO on your\r\n nick.  You can hide your E-mail address (EMAIL), last seen\r\n user@host mask (USERMASK), your services access status\r\n (STATUS) and  last quit message (QUIT).\r\n The second parameter specifies whether the information should\r\n be displayed (OFF) or hidden (ON).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET ICQ[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET ICQ number\r\n \r\n Associates the given ICQ number with your nickname.  This\r\n number will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET GREET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET GREET message\r\n \r\n Makes the given message the greet of your nickname, that\r\n will be displayed when joining a channel that has GREET\r\n option enabled, provided that you have the necessary\r\n access on it.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET KILL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET KILL {ON | QUICK | IMMED | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns the automatic protection option for your nick\r\n on or off.  With protection on, if another user\r\n tries to take your nick, they will be given one minute to\r\n change to another nick, after which NickServ will forcibly change\r\n their nick.\r\n \r\n If you select QUICK, the user will be given only 20 seconds\r\n to change nicks instead of the usual 60.  If you select\r\n IMMED, user\'s nick will be changed immediately without being\r\n warned first or given a chance to change their nick; please\r\n do not use this option unless necessary.  Also, your\r\n network\'s administrators may have disabled this option.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET SECURE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET SECURE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns NickServ\'s security features on or off for your\r\n nick.  With SECURE set, you must enter your password\r\n before you will be recognized as the owner of the nick,\r\n regardless of whether your address is on the access\r\n list.  However, if you are on the access list, NickServ\r\n will not auto-kill you regardless of the setting of the\r\n KILL option.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET PRIVATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PRIVATE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Turns NickServ\'s privacy option on or off for your nick.\r\n With PRIVATE set, your nickname will not appear in\r\n nickname lists generated with NickServ\'s LIST command.\r\n (However, anyone who knows your nickname can still get\r\n information on it using the INFO command.)[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET MSG[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET MSG {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Allows you to choose the way Services are communicating with\r\n you. With MSG set, Services will use messages, else they\'ll\r\n use notices.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]UPDATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  UPDATE\r\n Updates your current status, i.e. it checks for new memos,\r\n sets needed chanmodes (ModeonID) and updates your vhost and\r\n your userflags (lastseentime, etc).[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]RECOVER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RECOVER nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Allows you to recover your nickname if someone else has\r\n taken it; this does the same thing that NickServ does\r\n automatically if someone tries to use a kill-protected\r\n nick.\r\n \r\n When you give this command, NickServ will bring a fake\r\n user online with the same nickname as the user you\'re\r\n trying to recover your nick from.  This causes the IRC\r\n servers to disconnect the other user.  This fake user will\r\n remain online for NickServ to ensure that the other\r\n user does not immediately reconnect; after that time, you\r\n can reclaim your nick.  Alternatively, use the RELEASE\r\n command (/msg NickServ HELP RELEASE) to get the nick\r\n back sooner.\r\n \r\n In order to use the RECOVER command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]RELEASE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RELEASE nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Instructs NickServ to remove any hold on your nickname\r\n caused by automatic kill protection or use of the RECOVER\r\n command.  This holds lasts for NickServ;\r\n this command gets rid of them sooner.\r\n \r\n In order to use the RELEASE command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]GHOST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GHOST nickname [password]\r\n \r\n Terminates a \"ghost\" IRC session using your nick.  A\r\n \"ghost\" session is one which is not actually connected,\r\n but which the IRC server believes is still online for one\r\n reason or another.  Typically, this happens if your\r\n computer crashes or your Internet or modem connection\r\n goes down while you\'re on IRC.\r\n \r\n In order to use the GHOST command for a nick, your\r\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\r\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\r\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\r\n the nickname.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]INFO[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  INFO nickname [ALL]\r\n \r\n Displays information about the given nickname, such as\r\n the nick\'s owner, last seen address and time, and nick\r\n options. If you are identified for the nick you\'re\r\n getting information for and ALL is specified, you will\r\n be shown all the information; regardless of whether\r\n it\'s hidden or not.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LIST pattern\r\n \r\n Lists all registered nicknames which match the given\r\n pattern, in nick!user@host format.  Nicks with the\r\n PRIVATE option set will not be displayed.\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     LIST *!joeuser@foo.com\r\n         Lists all nicks owned by joeuser@foo.com.\r\n \r\n     LIST *Bot*!*@*\r\n         Lists all registered nicks with Bot in their\r\n         names (case insensitive).\r\n \r\n     LIST *!*@*.bar.org\r\n         Lists all nicks owned by users in the bar.org\r\n         domain.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]ALIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ALIST [level]\r\n \r\n Lists all channels you have access on. Optionally, you can specify\r\n a level in XOP or ACCESS format. The resulting list will only\r\n include channels where you have the given level of access.\r\n\r\n Examples:\r\n     ALIST Founder\r\n         Lists all channels where you have Founder\r\n         access.\r\n\r\n     ALIST AOP\r\n         Lists all channels where you have AOP\r\n         access or greater.\r\n\r\n     ALIST 10\r\n         Lists all channels where you have level 10\r\n         access or greater.\r\n\r\n Channels that have the NOEXPIRE option set will be\r\n prefixed by an exclamation mark.[/quote]\r\n[b]GLIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GLIST\r\n \r\n Lists all nicks in your group.[/quote]\r\n[b]STATUS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  STATUS nickname...\r\n \r\n Returns whether the user using the given nickname is\r\n recognized as the owner of the nickname.  The response has\r\n this format:\r\n \r\n     nickname status-code\r\n \r\n where nickname is the nickname sent with the command, and\r\n status-code is one of the following:\r\n \r\n     0 - no such user online or nickname not registered\r\n     1 - user not recognized as nickname\'s owner\r\n     2 - user recognized as owner via access list only\r\n     3 - user recognized as owner via password identification\r\n \r\n Up to sixteen nicknames may be sent with each command; the\r\n rest will be ignored. If no nickname is given, your status\r\n will be returned.[/quote]','2012-09-11 15:36:14'),(82,1,8,'irc_operator_staff',500,'B. IRC Operator Manual','IRC Operator Manual for Staff','[b][align=center][size=2]IRC Operator Manual[/size][/align][/b]\r\n\r\nThis is a simplified manual. There is a complete reference guide for more in depth documents. \r\n\r\n[bg=grey,310px,left][color=white][font=Tahoma][size=4][align=center][b]Chapters[/b][/align][/size][/font][/color]\r\n[bg=white,300px][bg=270px]\r\n[url=#botcommands]Bot commands[/url]\r\n[url=#annoying]How to deal with annoying users[/url]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n\r\n[#=botcommands][size=2][b]Bot commands.[/b][/size][/#]\r\n\r\nFantasy commands allows you to use simple shortcuts in place of many of the NickServ, ChanServ, and BotServ commands. \r\n\r\n[b]Moderator Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!INVITE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !INVITE\r\n \r\n  Invites \'nick\' to the channel if the user is present on the network.\r\n  N.B. This is the only way to invite someone to an official empornium channel.\r\n \r\n[b]!UP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UP [nick]\r\n \r\n Gives the user the modes he has rights to. This will unset modes if he has any\r\n the user has no access to.\r\n \r\n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \r\n a Services Root Administrator.\r\n \r\n[b]!DOWN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DOWN [nick]\r\n\r\n Does the opposite of the !up command\r\n \r\n[b]!KICK[/b]\r\n Syntax: !KICK [nick [reason]]\r\n \r\n Kick a user from the channel.\r\n \r\n[b]!KB[/b]\r\n Syntax: {!KICKBAN | !KB} [nick!]ident@host] [reason]\r\n \r\n This will kick and ban the specified user or all users matching the given \r\n mask from the channel. If a mask is given and someone who should not be \r\n kicked according to the channels\' settings matches it, the command is \r\n aborted before anyone is kicked or banned.\r\n \r\n[b]!TKB[/b]\r\n Syntax: !tkb or !tkban [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time] [reason]\r\n \r\n This will kick and temporarily ban the specified user\r\n\r\n Also be aware that this command may not work with IPs for privacy reasons.\r\n\r\n If the time is not given or is invalid, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n \r\n Example: !tkb SillyTroll 10m Bye \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n\r\n[b]!BAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !BAN [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Bans user from the channel without kicking.\r\n \r\n[b]!TBAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: {!TB | !TBAN} [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time]\r\n \r\n This will ban the given nick or hostmask from the channel for the specified\r\n amount of time. If the time is not given, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n \r\n Example: !tb SillyTroll 10m \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n \r\n Note: if services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\r\n not be automatically removed\r\n\r\n[b]!UNBAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UNBAN [nick | [nick!]ident@host]\r\n \r\n  Removes the ban on a user.\r\n \r\n[b]!MUTE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !MUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Bans or mutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n \r\n[b]!UNMUTE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UNMUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n \r\n Unbans or unmutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n \r\n[b]Admin Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!ACCESS[/b]\r\nÂ Syntax: !ACCESS add nick level\r\nÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â       !ACCESS del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\nÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â       !ACCESS list [mask | list]\r\nÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â       !ACCESS clear\r\nÂ \r\nÂ Maintains the access list for a channel. Â The access\r\nÂ list specifies which users are allowed chanop status or\r\nÂ access to commands on the channel.\r\nÂ \r\nTo add a mod: !access add nickname 5\r\nTo add a FLS: !access add nickname 4\r\nTo add a user to to autovoice: !access add nickname 3\r\n\r\nN.B. only users who have registered can be added to the access lists.\r\n\r\n[b]!AKICK[/b]\r\nÂ Syntax: !AKICK add {mask | user} [reason]\r\nÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â        !AKICK {list | view} [mask]\r\nÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â        !AKICK {enforce | clear}\r\nÂ \r\nÂ Maintains the channel auto-kick list (people who match this list will not be able to join the channel at all).\r\n\r\nExamples:\r\n!akick add GaryE bye\r\n!akick del Barumba\r\nÂ \r\n[b]!TOPIC[/b]\r\nÂ Syntax: !TOPIC [topic]\r\n\r\nÂ Sets the channel topic. If no topic is given, the currentÂ \r\nÂ topic is displayed in the channel.\r\nÂ \r\nÂ The CTOPIC command clears the topic.\r\nÂ \r\n[b]!TAPPEND[/b]\r\nÂ Syntax: {!TAPPEND Â | !APPENDTOPIC} Â text to be appended to topic\r\nÂ \r\nÂ Appends the given text to the channel\'s current topic. (only use if you need to add emergency information to the topic e.g. site going offline for a few days)\r\n\r\n[b]Announce Commands (only work in #empornium-announce)[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!EMPORNIUM[/b]\r\n Syntax: !EMPORNIUM\r\n \r\n Displays the last 5 torrents uploaded to torrents.empornium.me\r\n\r\n[b]Staff Commands (only work in #empornium-staff)[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]@@[/b]\r\n Syntax: @@ [optional comment]\r\n \r\n Adds a hilight line to the staff IRC logs. To access the [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=3065]logs check out this thread.[/url]\r\n\r\n[b]!SITESTATUS[/b]\r\n Syntax: !sitestatus\r\n \r\n Uses isup.me to check the status of torrent.empornium.me\r\n\r\n[#=annoying][size=2][b]How to deal with annoying users.[/b][/size][/#]\r\n\r\nIf a user is being aggressive toward others, being a nuisance, disruptive, trolling, breaking rules, spamming in the channel and/or advertising excessively, give them a warning first. \r\n\r\nIf they persist use: \r\n\r\n[b]!kick nickname [reason for kick][/b]\r\n\r\nThis will kick t he user out of the channel once. He can come back right away.\r\n\r\nIf they still continue use: \r\n\r\n[b]!tkb nickname 1d [/b]\r\n\r\nThis will kick the user out of the channel and ban him for one day.\r\n\r\nif they evade the ban report it to either barumba, clownius, or MrRandom who will add a network wide ban.\r\n\r\nIf a user PM\'s you continually, direct them to an appropriate channel (e.g. #empornium-help, #empornium, etc). If they continue and you use a client use the /ignore feature which is included in all major clients. If you use the webchat message barumba, clownius or MrRandom who will disconnect the user from the network.\r\n\r\nSilencing Users:\r\n\r\nWhen you silence a user, you allow the person to stay in the channel, but block the personâ€™s ability to participate in the discussion or change nicks. Itâ€™s an online equivalent of a short timeout, where the person has to sit quietly for several minutes before rejoining discussion.\r\n\r\nTo silence a user, youâ€™d type:\r\n\r\n[b]!mute nickname[/b]\r\n\r\nThat command sets a bans, ~q:nick!ident@user.host which prevents the user from participating in the discussion (unless the user is +v or higher, this will be autoremoved when you use the command). The ~q stands for quiet.\r\n\r\nTo remove a silence ban:\r\n\r\n[b]!unmute nickname[/b]\r\n\r\nEverything is the same. Youâ€™re just removing the ban.\r\n\r\nN.B. When a user gets unmuted they will not get revoiced if they were voiced before they were muted.\r\n ','2012-09-21 20:31:26'),(83,1,8,'irc_reference_staff',500,'C. IRC Operator Reference','IRC Operator Reference Manual for Staff','[b][align=center][size=2]IRC Operator Reference[/size][/align][/b]\r\n\r\n\r\n[bg=grey,50%,left][color=white][size=4][align=center][b]Contents[/b][/align][/size][/color]\r\n[bg=white,97%][bg=100%]\r\n[b][size=3][u]Sections[/u][/size][/b]\r\n\r\n[bg=grey,98%,center]\r\n[url=#oper][size=3][align=left][u]Oper Commands[/u][/align][/size][/url]\r\n[bg=white,96%]\r\n[align=left][url=#oper-alert]Alerting Other Opers[/url]\r\n[url=#oper-kills]Removing Users and/or banning them from the network[/url]\r\n[url=#oper-change]Changing information about You or another user[/url]\r\n[url=#oper-server]Commends used for server maintenance[/url][/align]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n\r\n[bg=grey,98%,center]\r\n[url=#bot][size=3][align=left][u]Bot Commands[/u][/align][/size][/url]\r\n[bg=white,96%]\r\n[align=left][url=#bot-general]Genreal Bot Commands[/url]\r\n[url=#bot-access]Access Bot Commands[/url]\r\n[url=#bot-channel]Channel Action Commands[/url]\r\n[url=#bot-mode]Channel Modes Commands[/url]\r\n[url=#bot-emp]Empornium Specific Commands[/url][/align]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n\r\n[bg=grey,98%,center]\r\n[url=#services][size=3][align=left][u]Channel Registration & management[/u][/align][/size][/url]\r\n[bg=white,96%]\r\n[align=left][url=#chan-register]How to register a channel[/url]\r\n[url=#chan-hide]How to hide a channel[/url]\r\n[url=#chan-password]Password protect a channel[/url]\r\n[url=#chan-mode]List of Channel Modes[/url]\r\n[url=#user-mode]List of User Modes[/url]\r\n[url=#chan-flood]Protecting from channel floods[/url]\r\n[url=#ban-options]Different banning options [/url][/align]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n[/bg]\r\n\r\n[#=oper][/#][size=3][b]Full list of operator commands[/b][/size]\r\n\r\n\r\n[b]OPER[/b]\r\n Syntax: /OPER userid password\r\n \r\n Command to give a user operator status if they match an\r\n Oper Block\r\n \r\n[#=oper-alert][/#][b]WALLOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /WALLOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all users with umode +w\r\n \r\n[b]GLOBOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GLOBOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all global IRCops\r\n \r\n[b]CHATOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHATOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all IRCops (local and global)\r\n \r\n[b]LOCOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: /LOCOPS message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all local IRCops\r\n \r\n[b]ADCHAT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADCHAT message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all Admins\r\n \r\n[b]NACHAT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /NACHAT message\r\n \r\n Sends a message to all Net Admins\r\n \r\n[#=oper-kill][/#][b]KILL[/b]\r\n Syntax: /KILL nick reason\r\n \r\n Kills a user from the network\r\n \r\n[b]KLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /KLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Bans the hostmask from the server it is issued on. A\r\n kline is not a global ban.   time to ban is\r\n either: a) a value in seconds, b) a time value, like\r\n \'1d\' is 1 day or c) \'0\' for permanent.  Time and reason\r\n are optional, if unspecified set::default-bantime\r\n (default: 0/permanent) and \'no reason\' are used.  To\r\n remove a kline use /kline -user@host\r\n \r\n[b]ZLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Bans an IP Address from the local server it is issued\r\n on (not global). See kline for more syntax info.   Use\r\n /zline -*@ip to remove.\r\n \r\n[b]GLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\r\n \r\n Adds a global ban to anyone that matches. See kline for\r\n more syntax info.      Use /gline -user@host to remove.\r\n \r\n[b]SHUN[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SHUN [+|-]user@host | nick [time to shun reason]\r\n \r\n Prevents a user from executing ANY commands and\r\n prevents them from speaking. Shuns are global (like\r\n glines). See kline for more syntax info. Use /shun\r\n -user@host to remove a shun.\r\n \r\n[b]GZLINE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /GZLINE [+|-]ip time to ban :reason\r\n \r\n Adds a global zline. See kline for more syntax info.\r\n   Use /gzline -*@ip to remove a gzline.\r\n\r\n[#=oper-change][/#][b]SETHOST[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SETHOST newhost\r\n \r\n Lets you change your vhost to what ever you want it to\r\n be.\r\n \r\n[b]SETIDENT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SETIDENT newident\r\n \r\n Lets you set your ident to what ever you want it to be\r\n \r\n[b]CHGHOST[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGHOST nick newhost\r\n \r\n Lets you change the host name of a user currently on\r\n the system\r\n \r\n[b]CHGIDENT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGIDENT nick newident\r\n \r\n Lets you change the ident of a user currently on the\r\n system\r\n \r\n[b]CHGNAME[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CHGNAME nick newname\r\n \r\n Lets you change the realname of a user currently on the\r\n system\r\n \r\n[#=oper-server][/#][b]REHASH[/b]\r\n Syntax: /REHASH server â€“flags\r\n \r\n Rehashes the servers config file. Including a server\r\n name allows you to rehash a remote servers config file.\r\n Several flags are also available. They Include \r\n -motd - Only rehash all MOTD and RULES files (including tld {})\r\n -opermotd - Only rehash the OPERMOTD file\r\n -botmotd - Only rehash the BOTMOTD file\r\n -garbage - Force garbage collection \r\n -global - Rehashes the configs of every server\r\n\r\n[b]SQUIT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SQUIT server\r\n \r\n Disconnects a server from the network\r\n DO NOT USE UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT YOU\'RE DOING\r\n \r\n[b]CONNECT[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CONNECT server port server\r\n \r\n If only one server is given, it will attempt to connect\r\n the server you are ON to the given server. If 2 servers\r\n are given, it will attempt to connect the 2 servers\r\n together. Put the leaf server as the first, and the hub\r\n server as the second.\r\n \r\n[b]DCCDENY[/b]\r\n Syntax: /DCCDENY filemask reason\r\n \r\n Adds a DCCDENY for that filemask. Preventing that file\r\n from being sent.\r\n \r\n[b]UNDCCDENY[/b]\r\n Syntax: /UNDCCDENY filemask\r\n \r\n Removes a DCCDENY\r\n \r\n[b]RPING[/b]\r\n Syntax: /RPING servermask\r\n \r\n Will calculate in milliseconds the lag between servers\r\n \r\n[b]TRACE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /TRACE servermask|nickname\r\n \r\n When used on a user it will give you class and lag\r\n info. If you use  it on a server it gives you\r\n class/version/link info.\r\n \r\n[b]OPERMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /OPERMOTD\r\n \r\n Displays the servers OperMotd File\r\n \r\n[b]ADDMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADDMOTD :text\r\n \r\n Will add the given text to the end of the Motd\r\n \r\n[b]ADDOMOTD[/b]\r\n Syntax: /ADDOMOTD :text\r\n \r\n Will add the given text to the end of the OperMotd\r\n \r\n[b]SDESC[/b]\r\n Syntax: /SDESC newdescription\r\n \r\n Allows server admins to change the description line of\r\n their server without restarting.\r\n  \r\n[b]CLOSE[/b]\r\n Syntax: /CLOSE\r\n \r\n This command will disconnect all unknown connections\r\n from the IRC server.\r\n\r\n[#=bot][/#][size=3][b]Full list of bot commands[/b][/size]\r\n\r\n[#=bot-general][/#][b]General Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!HELP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !HELP\r\n\r\n Help for BotServ fantasy commands\r\n\r\n[b]!CMDLIST[/b]\r\n Syntax: !CMDLIST\r\n\r\n  A list of all available fantasy commands\r\n\r\n[b]!IRCOPS[/b]\r\n Syntax: !IRCOPS\r\n\r\n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window (It will not show empornium staff)\r\n\r\n[b]!STAFF[/b]\r\n Syntax: !STAFF\r\n\r\n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window (It will not show empornium staff)\r\n\r\n[b]!INFO[/b]\r\n Syntax: !INFO [ALL]\r\n\r\n  Shows information about the channel. \r\n The \'all\' option is limited to founders and Services Admins.\r\n\r\n[#=bot-access][/#][b]Access Control Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!ACCESS[/b]\r\n Syntax: !ACCESS add nick level\r\n         !ACCESS del {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         !ACCESS list [mask | list]\r\n         !ACCESS clear\r\n\r\n Maintains the access list for a channel.  The access\r\n list specifies which users are allowed chanop status or\r\n access to commands on the channel.\r\n\r\n Different user levels allow for access to different subsets of\r\n privileges; cf. /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more specific \r\n information. Any nick not on the access list has a user level of 0.\r\n\r\n[b]!LEVELS[/b]\r\n Syntax: !LEVELS set type level\r\n         !LEVELS {dis | disable} type\r\n         !LEVELS list\r\n         !LEVELS reset\r\n\r\n The LEVELS command allows fine control over the meaning of\r\n the numeric access levels used for the channel.  With this command,\r\n you can define the access level required for most administrative functions.\r\n (The SET FOUNDER and SET PASSWORD commands, as well as this command, \r\n are always restricted to the channel founder.) \r\n\r\n LEVELS SET allows the access level for a function or group of \r\n functions to be changed.\r\n\r\n LEVELS DISABLE (or DIS for short) disables an automatic\r\n feature or disallows access to a function by anyone other \r\n than the channel founder.\r\n\r\n LEVELS LIST shows the current levels for each function or group\r\n  of functions.\r\n\r\n LEVELS RESET resets the levels to the default levels of a \r\n newly-created channel.\r\n\r\n (See /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more info.)\r\n\r\n For a list of the features and functions whose levels can be\r\n set, see HELP LEVELS DESC.\r\n\r\n[b]Channel Setting Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!AKICK[/b]\r\n Syntax: !AKICK add {mask | user} [reason]\r\n         !AKICK {stick | unstick | del} mask\r\n         !AKICK {list | view} [mask]\r\n         !AKICK {enforce | clear}\r\n\r\n Maintains the channel AKICK list. See the ChanServ AKICK command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!SET[/b]\r\n Syntax: !SET option parameters\r\n\r\n Changes channel\'s settings. \r\n\r\n Available options:\r\n See the ChanServ SET command for more details on the following:\r\n   founder       -  Set the founder of a channel\r\n   successor     -  Set the successor for a channel\r\n   desc          -  Set the channel description\r\n   url           -  Associate a URL with the channel\r\n   email         -  Associate an E-mail address with the channel\r\n   entrymsg      -  Set a message to be sent to users when they enter the \r\n                    channel\r\n   bantype       -  Set how Services make bans on the channel\r\n   mlock         -  Lock channel modes on or off\r\n   keeptopic     -  Retain topic when channel is not in use\r\n   topiclock     -  Topic can only be changed with TOPIC\r\n   opnotice      -  Send a notice when OP/DEOP commands are used\r\n   peace         -  Regulate the use of critical commands\r\n   private       -  Hide channel from LIST command\r\n   restricted    -  restrict access to the channel\r\n   secure        -  activate services\' security features\r\n   secureops     -  stricter control of chanop status\r\n   securefounder -  stricter control of channel founder status\r\n   signkick      -  Sign kicks that are done with KICK command\r\n   xop           -  Toggle the user privilege system\r\n\r\n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following:\r\n   noexpire      -  Sets whether the given channel will expire. \r\n                    (limited to SA)\r\n   dontkickops   -  Protect channel ops against kicks by the services bot.\r\n   dontkickvoices - Protect voices against kicks by the services bot.\r\n   greet         -  Enable greet messages on join.\r\n   fantasy       -  Enable fantasy commands on the channel.\r\n   symbiosis     -  Allow the bot to act as a real bot.\r\n   nobot         -  Prevents a bot from being assigned to this channel. \r\n                    (limited to SA)\r\n\r\n[b]!BKICK[/b]\r\n Syntax: !BKICK option {on | off} [ttb [params]]\r\n\r\n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following options:\r\n\r\n   bolds       -  Sets whether the bot kicks bolds.\r\n   badwords    -  Sets whether the bots kicks for words in  \r\n                  the badwords list.\r\n   caps        -  Sets whether the bot kicks for CAPS.\r\n   colors      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for colors.\r\n   flood       -  Sets whether the bot kicks for floods.\r\n   repeat      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for repeats.\r\n   reverses    -  Sets whether the bot kicks for reverses.\r\n   underlines  -  Sets whether the bot kicks for underlines.\r\n\r\n ttb is the number of times a user can be kicked before he gets banned.\r\n Don\'t give ttb to disable the ban system once activated.\r\n\r\n[#=bot-channel][/#][b]Channel Action Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!CLEAR[/b]\r\n Syntax: !CLEAR {modes | bans | excepts | invites | ops | hops | voices | users}\r\n\r\n Clears the specified option on the channel. \r\n See the ChanServ CLEAR command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!TOPIC[/b]\r\n Syntax: !TOPIC [topic]\r\n         !CTOPIC\r\n Sets the channel topic. If no topic is given, the current \r\n topic is displayed in the channel.\r\n\r\n The CTOPIC command clears the topic.\r\n\r\n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK \r\n\r\n See the ChanServ TOPIC command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!TAPPEND[/b]\r\n Syntax: {!TAPPEND  | !APPENDTOPIC}  text to be appended to topic\r\n\r\n Appends the given text to the channel\'s current topic.\r\n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK\r\n\r\n[b]!INVITE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !INVITE\r\n\r\n  Invites \'nick\' to the channel if the user is present on the network.\r\n\r\n[b]!UP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UP\r\n\r\n Gives the user the modes he has rights to. This will unset modes if he has any\r\n the user has no access to.\r\n\r\n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \r\n a Services Root Administrator.\r\n\r\n[b]!DOWN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DOWN [nick] [level]\r\n\r\n Unsets all modes. If the channel is moderated, it will reset voice,\r\n unless issued on another user by a founder. It is also possible\r\n to specify a target level. \r\n\r\n The target level can be any one of the following:\r\n\r\n    - q - Channel founder (modes +qo) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - a - Protected Operator / Administrator (modes +ao) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - o - Channel Operator (mode +o)\r\n    - h - Channel Halfop (mode +h) (IRCd Dependant)\r\n    - v - \\\"Voice\\\" (mode +v)\r\n\r\n If a target level is specified, the users\' current privileges will be  \r\n replaced by the target one.\r\n\r\n[b]!KICK[/b]\r\n Syntax: !KICK [nick [reason]]\r\n\r\n Kick a user from the channel.\r\n See the ChanServ KICK command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!KB[/b]\r\n Syntax: {!KICKBAN | !KB} [nick!]ident@host] [reason]\r\n\r\n This will kick and ban the specified user or all users matching the given \r\n mask from the channel. If a mask is given and someone who should not be \r\n kicked according to the channels\' settings matches it, the command is \r\n aborted before anyone is kicked or banned.\r\n\r\n[b]!TKB[/b]\r\n Syntax: !tkb or !tkban [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time] [reason]\r\n\r\n This will kick and temporarily ban the specified user or all users matching\r\n the given mask from the channel for the specified amount of time. \r\n\r\n If a mask is given and someone who should not be banned according to the\r\n channels\' settings matches it, the command is aborted before anyone is \r\n kicked.\r\n\r\n Also be aware that this command may not work with IPs for privacy reasons.\r\n\r\n If the time is not given or is invalid, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n\r\n Example: !tkb SillyTroll 10m Bye \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n\r\n Note: if Services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\r\n not be automatically removed.\r\n\r\n[#=bot-mode][/#][b]Channel Modes Commands[/b]\r\n\r\n[b]!BAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !BAN [nick | mask]\r\n\r\n Bans (a) user(s)/mask from the channel without kicking.\r\n\r\n[b]!TBAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: {!TB | !TBAN} [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time]\r\n\r\n This will ban the given nick or hostmask from the channel for the specified\r\n amount of time. If the time is not given, it will default to 1 hour.\r\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\r\n\r\n Example: !tb SillyTroll 10m \r\n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\r\n\r\n Note: if services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\r\n not be automatically removed\r\n\r\n[b]!UNBAN[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UNBAN [nick | [nick!]ident@host]\r\n\r\n  Removes the ban on a user.\r\n\r\n[b]!MUTE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !MUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n\r\n Bans or mutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!UNMUTE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !UNMUTE  [nick | mask]\r\n\r\n Unbans or unmutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \r\n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!OP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !OP  [nick]\r\n\r\n Op yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ OP command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!DEOP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DEOP  [nick]\r\n\r\n Deop yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ OP command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!VOICE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !VOICE [nick]\r\n\r\n Voice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ VOICE command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!DEVOICE[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DEVOICE [nick]\r\n\r\n Devoice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEVOICE command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!PROTECT[/b]\r\n Syntax: !PROTECT [nick]\r\n\r\n Protect yourself or another user (so you cannot be kicked). See \r\n the ChanServ PROTECT command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!DEPROTECT[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DEPROTECT [nick]\r\n\r\n Remove protection from  yourself or another user. See the \r\n ChanServ DEPROTECT command for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!OWNER[/b]\r\n Syntax: !OWNER\r\n\r\n Give yourself the owner mode. See the ChanServ OWNER command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!DEOWNER[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DEOWNER\r\n\r\n Remove the owner mode. See the ChanServ DEOWNER command for \r\n more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!HALFOP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !HALFOP [nick]\r\n\r\n Halfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ HALFOP command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[b]!DEHALFOP[/b]\r\n Syntax: !DEHALFOP [nick]\r\n\r\n Dehalfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEHALFOP command \r\n for more details.\r\n\r\n[#=bot-emp][/#][size=3][b]Empornium Specific Commands[/b][/size]\r\n\r\n[b]Announce Commands[/b] (only work in #empornium-announce)\r\n\r\n[b]!EMPORNIUM[/b]\r\nSyntax: !EMPORNIUM\r\n\r\nDisplays the last 5 torrents uploaded to torrents.empornium.me\r\n\r\n[b]Staff Commands[/b] (only work in #empornium-staff)\r\n\r\n[b]@@[/b]\r\nSyntax: @@ [optional comment]\r\n\r\nAdds a hilight line to the staff IRC logs. To access the logs check out this thread.\r\n\r\n[b]!SITESTATUS[/b]\r\nSyntax: !sitestatus\r\n\r\nUses isup.me to check the status of torrent.empornium.me\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=services][/#][size=3][b]Channel Registration and Management Information[/b][/size]\r\n\r\n[#=chan-register][/#][b]Registering A Channel[/b]\r\n\r\n\r\nRegistering your channel on Empornium IRC gives you many advantages, and is completely free. These include:\r\n\r\nIncreased control over your channel\r\nAbility to add people to the auto op list\r\nAbility to add auto kicks\r\nAbility to use a services bot to auto moderate your channel\r\nAnd many many moreâ€¦\r\nTo register your channel, you must first register your nickname. To do this, when you are using the nickname that you wish to register, type the following command into your IRC client:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register password e-mail[/quote]\r\n\r\nYou must replace password and e-mail with a real password and e-mail address, respectively. An example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/ns register supersecretpassword fred@hotmail.com[/quote]\r\n\r\nIt is important that you use your real e-mail address as this will be used in future if you ever forget your password. We will not send any unsolicited e-mail to this address.\r\n\r\nOnce you have registered your nickname, you can register your channel. All channels names begin with the # symbol, for example #help, #chris and #247fixes. Once you have picked a channel name, you can join it using the command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #channel[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #chat[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you have joined the channel, if it is not already registered, you should see your name in the nickname list with the @ symbol next to it. This means you are an operator in the channel. You may now register it with the following command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/cs register #channel password description[/quote]\r\n\r\nYou must replace #channel, password and description with the channel name, the channel password and a description of the channel. An example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/cs register #chat verysecretpassword Freds chat channel[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you have done that, you should see your name in the nick list prefixed with the ~ symbol. This means you are the owner of the channel.\r\n\r\nOn Empornium IRC a Services Bot will automatically be assigned to your channel. You can change or remove it later.\r\n\r\n[#=chan-hide][/#][b]Hide your Channel[/b]\r\n\r\nSecret vs. Private:\r\n\r\nThere are two modes you can use to hide your channel: [b]+s[/b], for a secret channel; and [b]+p[/b], for a private channel.\r\n\r\nOriginally (that is, in earlier days of IRC), there was a difference between these two modes. On Empornium IRC, the two commands do the same thing. If you set your channel to [b]+p[/b] or to [b]+s[/b], your channel will not show up in the channel listing that someone gets after using the /LIST command and in a /WHOIS list for a user who is in the channel (unless the person using the command is also in the secret channel)\r\n\r\nSince the two commands do the same thing, you can only set one or the other.\r\n\r\nSetting the Secret or Private Mode:\r\n\r\nTo set the secret mode, use this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel +s[/quote]\r\n\r\nIn that command, replace \"channel\" with your #channel. For instance, for my super-secret channel, I used this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +s[/quote] \r\n\r\nTo set the private mode, use this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel +p[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor instance, I used this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +p[/quote]\r\n  \r\nRestrictions on the +s and +p Modes:\r\n\r\nIf you set your channel to +s and then decide to set +p, the server will respond by removing the +s setting. Youâ€™d see something like this:\r\n\r\n[quote]* MrRandom sets mode: +s\r\n* MrRandom sets mode: +p-s[/quote]\r\n\r\nIn the second line, the server set +p (adding the private setting), and [b]-s[/b] (removing the secret setting). This is normal. Since the commands do the same thing, you only need one or the other (never both). As long as you have the channel set to [b]+s[/b] or to [b]+p[/b], it will be hidden.\r\n\r\nRemoving the Secret or Private Mode:\r\n\r\nIf you no longer want your channel to be hidden, you can remove the secret or private mode easily:\r\n\r\nTo remove the secret mode, use this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel -s[/quote]\r\n\r\nTo remove the private mode, use this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel -p[/quote]\r\n\r\nOnce you remove the setting, your channel will be visible to everyone on the network.\r\n\r\nTwo Tips on Using the Secret or Private Mode:\r\n\r\nRemember that even though your channel is hidden, the people you ask to join you in the channel can tell others about it. Only invite people to join your channel if you trust them to maintain your privacy. If you cannot trust someone not to tell others about the space, donâ€™t ask them to join your channel.\r\n\r\nAny moderator (half-ops, ops, and admins) on your channel can change the channel mode. Donâ€™t add someone as a moderator in the channel if you cannot trust that person to leave the channel with the settings you want.\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=chan-password][/#][b][size=3]Channel Passwords[/size][/b]\r\n\r\nIf you ever had a secret password to get into your clubhouse, you understand the way that channel keys work. You can set a channel key for your channel, and only those people who have the key will be able to join the channel. If you want to have private conversations, using a channel key is a simple way to make it happen.\r\n\r\nSetting a Channel Key:\r\n\r\nTo set a channel key, use this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel +k channelkey[/quote] \r\n\r\nIn that command, replace \"channel\" with your #channel and replace \"channelkey\" with your channel key (your password). For instance, for my super-secret channel, I used this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +k nomnomnom [/quote] \r\n\r\nWhen you set a channel key, everyone in the channel will see the new key. When I set my channel key, for instance, the server announced this in the channel:\r\n\r\n * MrRandom sets mode: +k nomnomnom\r\n\r\nTips:\r\n\r\nBe sure that you choose a strong password that others will not easily guess. \r\n\r\nMake sure you remove anyone you do not want to have the key before you set it. You can ask him to leave OR kick and ban if necessary. Remember that the server announces the key in channel when you set it, so everyone in your channel will see the new key.\r\n\r\nAnyone who has half-op status or higher in your channel can change the channel key. If you cannot trust someone, donâ€™t make that person a moderator. He could easily change the password and lock everyone out of the channel! This can be fixed by doing [quote]/cs clear #channel modes[/quote]\r\n\r\nThe channel key will only remain as long as someone is in the channel. If everyone leaves, the next person who joins will be able to do so without knowing the channel key. The easiest solution to this problem is either to add a bnc user to the channel or create a private bot to occupy the channel. Note that services bots will not hold a channel open.\r\n\r\n\r\nJoining a Channel with a Key:\r\n\r\nYou need to provide the password to join your channel now once you set your key. Hereâ€™s how to use the JOIN command with a channel key:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #channel password[/quote]\r\n\r\nFor my super-secret channel, I used this command:\r\n\r\n[quote]/join #baconmylove nomnomnom[/quote]\r\n\r\nYouâ€™ll need to give your password and this command to everyone who you want to grant access to your channel. Only give your channel password to the people you trust with access to your private space.\r\n\r\nChanging your Channel Key:\r\n\r\nTo change your channel key, just use the same command with a new password:\r\n\r\n/mode #channel +k newchannelkey \r\nThe command is exactly the same. You just indicate the new channel key when you use the command.\r\n\r\nTroubleshooting:\r\n\r\nYou see this error message in your status window: #channel :Cannot join channel (+k)\r\nEither you didnâ€™t include the password or you used the wrong password. Check with the channel owner for the correct password or to ask for access to the channel.\r\n\r\nYou get locked out of your own channel.\r\nIf you forget your password or someone else changes it, you can just change your channel key and join with the new key. If a moderator in your channel changed the password without your permission, you may want to talk to that person or remove his access. Remember you should only add people as half-ops, ops, or admins if you trust them completely.\r\n\r\nIf you are an owner who gets locked out of your channel join the network help channel #silentzombies-help @ irc.emprn.tk they will help you get your channel back.\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=chan-mode][/#][size=3][b]Channel Modes[/b][/size]\r\n\r\nThis section lists all of the possible channel modes that may be used with /MODE\r\n\r\nAn example of the use of this command is: /mode #chills +o Brigitte\r\n\r\n[b]Mode[/b]\r\na = Gives Channel Admin to the user\r\nA = Server/Network Admin only channel (settable by Admins)\r\nb = Bans the nick!ident@host from the channel.\r\n       Extended bantypes are also available. (for more info see [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24642]Extended Bans Tutorial[/url]) [h]\r\nc = Block messages containing mIRC color codes [o]\r\nC = No CTCPs allowed in the channel [o]\r\ne = Overrides a ban for matching users [h]\r\nf = Flood protection (for more info see [url=#chan-flood]channel flood protection tutorial[/url]) [o]\r\nG = Filters out all Bad words in messages with [o]\r\nh = Gives HalfOp status to the user (Limited Channel operator access)\r\ni = A user must be invited to join the channel [h]\r\nI = Overrides +i for matching users [h]\r\nj = Throttle joins per-user to â€˜joinsâ€™ per â€˜secâ€™ seconds [o]\r\nk = Users must specify to join (for more info see [url=#chan-password]Using Channel Keys[/url]) [h]\r\nK = /KNOCK is not allowed [o]\r\nl = Channel may hold at most of users [o]\r\nL = Channel link (If +l is full, the next user will auto-join ) [q]\r\nm = Moderated channel (only +vhoaq users may speak) [h]\r\nM = Must be using a registered nick (+r), or have voice access to talk [o]\r\nn = Users outside the channel can not send PRIVMSGs to the channel [h]\r\nN = No Nickname changes are permitted in the channel [o]\r\no = Gives Channel Operator status to the user\r\nO = IRC Server Operator only channel (settable by IRCops)\r\np = Private channel (for more info see Using Channel Modes to [url=#chan-hide]Hide Your Channel[/url]) [o]\r\nq = Gives Owner status to the user\r\nQ = No kicks allowed [o]\r\nr = The channel is registered (settable by services only)\r\nR = Only registered (+r) users may join the channel [o]\r\ns = Secret channel (for more info see Using Channel Modes to [url=#chan-hide]Hide Your Channel[/url]) [o] \r\nS = Strips mIRC color codes [o]\r\nt = Only +hoaq may change the topic [h]\r\nT = No NOTICEs allowed in the channel [o]\r\nu = Auditorium mode (/names and /who #channel only show channel ops) [q]\r\nU = Block messages containing mIRC formatting codes [o]\r\nv = Gives Voice to the user (May talk if chan is +m)\r\nV = /INVITE is not allowed [o]\r\nz = Only Clients on a Secure Connection (SSL) can join [o]\r\n\r\n[b]Key[/b]\r\n[h] requires at least halfop\r\n[o] requires at least chanop\r\n[q] requires owner\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=user-mode][/#][b]User Modes[/b]\r\n\r\n\r\nHere is a list of all the user modes which are available for use. An example command for setting a mode on yourself is: /umode +D\r\n\r\n[b]Modes[/b]\r\n\r\na = Is a Services Administrator [o]\r\nA = Is a Server Administrator [o]\r\nB = Marks you as being a Bot [code][u][/code]\r\nC = Is a Co Administrator [o]\r\nd = Makes it so you can not receive channel PRIVMSGs (Deaf)\r\nD = Makes it so you cannot receive private PRIVMSGs (Deaf to PMs)\r\ng = Can read & send to GlobOps, and LocOps [o]\r\nG = Filters out all Bad words in your messages with <censored> [code][u][/code]\r\nh = Available for Help [h & o]\r\nH = Hide IRCop status in /WHO and /WHOIS. [o]\r\ni = Invisible (Not shown in /WHO searches) [Cannot be removed for security reasons]\r\nN = Is a Network Administrator (IRC Operators only)\r\no = Global IRC Operator (IRC Operators only)\r\nO = Local IRC Operator (IRC Operators only)\r\np = Hide all channels in /whois and /who\r\nq = Only U:lines can kick you (Services Admins/Net Admins only)\r\nr = Identifies the nick as being Registered (settable by services only)\r\nR = Allows you to only receive PRIVMSGs/NOTICEs from registered (+r) users\r\ns = Can listen to Server notices [Cannot be set  for security reasons]\r\nS = For Services only. (Protects them) [Cannot be set to any user or oper]\r\nt = Says that you are using a /VHOST [Cannot be set except by services]\r\nT = Prevents you from receiving CTCPs\r\nv = Receive infected DCC send rejection notices\r\nV = Marks the client as a WebTV user\r\nw = Can listen to Wallop messages\r\nW = Lets you see when people do a /WHOIS on you [o]\r\nx = Gives the user a hidden hostname (security)\r\nz = Marks the client as being on a Secure Connection (SSL) [Can only be set by connecting to port 6697]\r\n\r\n[b]Key[/b]\r\n\r\n[code][h][/code] requires being operator in the network help channel\r\n[code][o][/code] Can only be set by operator\r\n[code][u][/code] Can be set by any user\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=chan-flood][/#][b][size=3]Channel Flood Protection[/size][/b]\r\n\r\n\r\nThe +f channel mode provides comprehensive flood protection for a channel. This mode allows you to prevent join, nick change, CTCP, text, and knock floods. The syntax for this modeâ€™s parameter is as follows:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #channel +f [{#}{,...}]:[/quote]\r\n\r\nThe amount specifies the number of times the specified flood must occur before action is taken. \r\n\r\nBelow are the available types:\r\n\r\n[table]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] Type [/td][td] Name [/td][td] Default Action [/td][td] Other Actions [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] c [/td][td] CTCP [/td][td] +C (no channel CTCPs allowed) [/td][td] +m (only voiced users can speak), +M (only registered users can speak) [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] j [/td][td] Join [/td][td] +i (invite only) [/td][td] R (only registered users can join) [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] k [/td][td] Knock [/td][td] +K (no knocks allowed) [/td][td] None [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] m [/td][td] Message [/td][td] +m (only voiced users can speak) [/td][td] +M (only registered users can speak) [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] n [/td][td] Nickname Change [/td][td] +N (no nickname changes allowed) [/td][td] None [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[tr]\r\n[td] t [/td][td] text [/td][td] User is kicked from the channel [/td][td] +b (user is banned from the channel) [/td]\r\n[/tr]\r\n[/table]\r\n\r\nN.B. The difference between type [b]m[/b] and [b]t[/b] is that [b]m[/b] is tallied for the entire channel whereas [b]t[/b] is tallied per user.\r\n\r\nIf you choose to specify an action for a mode, you may also specify a time (in minutes) after which the specific action will be reversed.\r\n\r\nAn example of the use of this command is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #chills +f [2c#C5,6j#R3,3k#K10,15m#m5,5n#N3,5t#b60]:5[/quote]\r\n\r\nThis meansâ€¦\r\n\r\nIf there are 2 channel CTCP messages (2c) in 5 seconds(:5) set mode +C for 5 mins (#C5)\r\nIf there are 6 joins (6j) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +R for 3 mins (#R3)\r\nIf there are 3 /KNOCK commands on the channel (3k) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +K for 10 mins (#K10)\r\nIf there are 15 messages in total from all users (15m) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +m for 5 mins (#m5)\r\nIf there are 5 nickname changes (n5) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +N for 3 mins (#N3)\r\nIf there are 5 messages from any single user (5t) in 5 seconds (:5) ban the user for 60 mins (#b60)\r\n\r\n\r\nIt has been observed lately that bot nets are joining channels and rapidly joining and parting. In order to prevent this, you can use channel mode [b]j[/b]. This mode will allow only x joins to your channel in y seconds for each client. The recommended setting for this is 1 join in 1 second as this will entirely eradicate join/part flooding from botnets. An example of the use of this is:\r\n\r\n[quote]/mode #chills +j 1:1[/quote]\r\n\r\n[#=ban-options][/#][b][size=3]Different banning options Senior staff ONLY (e.g IRC Operators)[/size][/b]\r\n\r\nProceed with caution. If you are not sure consult the usual suspects.\r\n\r\n[b]KLine[/b]\r\n\r\n[quote]Syntax: /KLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time] <reason>\r\n \r\n  Example: /KLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\r\n \r\n Bans the hostmask from the server it is issued on. A\r\n kline is not a global ban.   time to ban is\r\n either: a) a value in seconds, b) a time value, like\r\n \'1d\' is 1 day or c) \'0\' for permanent.  Time and reason\r\n are optional, if unspecified a ban time of 7 days and \'no reason\' are used.  \r\n To remove a kline use /kline -user@host[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]GLine[/b]\r\n\r\n[quote]Syntax: /GLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time] <reason>\r\n\r\n  Example: /GLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse \r\n\r\n Adds a global ban to anyone that matches. See kline for\r\n more syntax info.      \r\n Use /gline -user@host to remove.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]ZLine[/b]\r\n\r\n[quote]Syntax: /ZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time] <reason>\r\n\r\n Example: /ZLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\r\n \r\n Bans an IP Address from the local server it is issued\r\n on (not global). See kline for more syntax info.  \r\n Use /zline -*@ip to remove.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]GZLine[/b]\r\n\r\n[quote]Syntax: /GZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time] <reason>\r\n\r\n Example: /GZLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\r\n \r\n Bans an IP Address from connecting to any server on the network.\r\n See kline for more syntax info.   \r\n Use /zline -*@ip to remove.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]How to set a vhost[/b] (For IRCOp\'s, mods and vhost setters)\r\n\r\nNew vhost requests will be announced in #opers when they are first send and then every hour afterwards, to set a vhost either use the in channel method\r\n\r\nTo accept a vhost:\r\n[quote]!vhost a [b]Nickname[/b][/quote]\r\nTo reject a vhost:\r\n[quote]!vhost r [b]Nickname[/b][/quote]\r\n\r\nIf you don\'t want to use the in channel method,\r\nTo accept:\r\n[quote]/hs a [b]nickname[/b][/quote]\r\nTo reject:\r\n[quote]/hs r [b]nickname[/b][/quote]\r\n','2012-09-21 20:32:01'),(84,1,8,'irc_guide_staff',500,'A.  IRC Guide for Staff','IRC Guide specific for Staff only','[b]0. Register[/b]\r\n\r\n[color=#FF0000]Now [b]very important[/b] type these commands in the status window as well as all involving your password. So if you mess up you do not show your password in the channel for all to see!![/color]\r\n\r\nSo first make sure you are using the nickname you want. if not you can change it with:\r\n\r\n[b]/nick <nickname>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample : /nick barumba_is_the_man\r\n\r\nThen register your nickname:\r\n\r\n[b]/ns register <password> <email>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample: /ns register empircisfun barumba@gmail.com\r\n\r\nmake sure you use a password you remember!\r\nyou will not get an email notifications. This will only be used to recover your password. \r\nOnce given that command you are done. And you need to do it only once.\r\nIf you mess up contact the staff and they can help you fix it.\r\n\r\n\r\n[b]1. Using the Webchat[/b] -> [color=#FF0000]not to state the obvious but.... you will make your life a LOT LOT LOT easier using a client instead.[/color]\r\n\r\nWith this option all you have to do is identify yourself in the [b]status window[/b]:\r\n\r\n[b]/ns identify <password>[/b]\r\n\r\nexample: /ns identify empircisfun\r\n\r\nthen use the [b]/join[/b] command in the [b]status window[/b]:\r\n\r\n/join #empornium-staff\r\n\r\nyou can do this manually but with the new webchat interface you can have it done for you.\r\n\r\nFirst you select the channel(s) you want to join:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=CC57_504BE3AA[/img]\r\n\r\nThen you select the Auth pull-down menu and input your password:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=4293_504BE3AA[/img]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n[b]2. Using mIRC[/b]\r\n\r\nIf you are not familiar with mIRC after getting it and installing it read the guide (no point in duplicating it, is good) : [url=http://www.mirc.com/install.html]Link to first use guide[/url]\r\n\r\nThe to connect to the staff channel you need to enable SSL in mIRC.\r\n\r\nGet and install OpenSSL 1.0.1c from here: [url=http://www.mirc.com/downloads/openssl/openssl-1.0.1c-setup.exe]openssl-1.0.1c-setup.exe[/url]\r\n\r\nLet it install in your System32 folder. Is OK this way SSL is available to all of your applications if needed. Including mIRC. You will see that mIRC is SSL enabled now going to [b]Tools [/b]then [b]Options [/b]and choosing [b]Options [/b]under [b]Connect[/b] and you will see the [b]SSL [/b]button is active (not grey anymore.\r\n\r\nClick it and in the windows from the pull down menu select [b]accept invalid certificates automatically[/b].\r\n\r\nThe add the empornium server like in the image below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=8DA7_50267CD4[/img]\r\n\r\nnotice the port is +6697. This is very important for all to work\r\n\r\nThen after you connect to the server and identify yourself you can access the staff forum with the /join command and then you can add it to your favorites, make it auto join, etc... as you like.\r\n\r\nThen in mIRC you can automate the identify. So you do not have to worry about it anymore.\r\n\r\nsimply go to [b]Tools [/b]then [b]Script Editor...[/b] and select the [b]Remote [/b]tab is is not.\r\n\r\nThen copy/paste this text in the window:\r\n\r\n[color=#0000FF]on 1:NOTICE:*This nickname is registered*:?: {\r\n  if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n    ns identify PASSWORD\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\non 1:NOTICE:*This nick is owned by someone else*:?: {\r\n  if ($nick == NickServ) {\r\n    ns identify PASSWORD\r\n  }\r\n}[/color]\r\n\r\nand change the two instances of PASSWORD to yours. Click OK and you are done!\r\n\r\n[b]3. Using Chatzilla[/b] \r\n\r\nChatzilla is a Firefox plug-in so it works on any OS where Firefox can be installed. You install it like any other plug-in and access it from the tools window. Then to access the Empornium IRC server type:\r\n\r\n/sslserver irc.emprn.tk 6697\r\n\r\nWhen you connect you will be warned that the server has an invalid certificate, click \"add exeption\" and remember to change your nickname to the one you use on the site and identify yourself. Then use the /join command.\r\n\r\nYou can automate the identification in Chatzilla preferences see below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=F16A_50269083[/img]\r\n\r\nand you can add channels for an auto-join when you start Chatzilla right click the channel tab and do as below:\r\n\r\n[img]http://xxx.freeimage.us/image.php?id=8B09_5026A1EF[/img]\r\n\r\n[b]4. XChat (thanks MrRandom for this)[/b]\r\n\r\nHow to connect with xchat (this tutorial also works for clients based off of xchat such as HexChat)\r\n\r\nFirstly we need to get xchat installed. For linux users it should be in your repository e.g. ubuntu is \"sudo apt-get install xchat\". If you are on windows you can grab it from [url=http://www.silverex.org/download/]here[/url].\r\n\r\nWhen you first run xchat you will be presented with a server connect list.\r\n\r\n[img]http://xchat.org/docs/start/xchat-1-servlist.png[/img]\r\n\r\nChange your nickname and real name settings. Then click add to add a new IRC network and change the name to \"Empornium IRC\" and hit enter.\r\n\r\n[img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/xchat_server_edit.PNG[/img]\r\n\r\nClick edit double click on \"newserver/6667\" and change it to \"irc.digitalwizardry.org/6697\", [color=#FF0000]once edited click somewhere else or it will not be saved![/color] Click the check boxes on Use SSL and Accept invalid SSL Certificate, and if you registered your nickname enter the password you used.\r\n\r\n[img]https://dl.dropbox.com/u/3012235/static/xchat_server_edit2.PNG[/img]\r\n\r\nClick the close button, then click connect and that\'s you you should be connected to Empornium IRC over secure SSL.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n[u][url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_Internet_Relay_Chat_clients]Here[/url][/u] you can find a very nice comparative list of the IRC clients available with lots of information.\r\n\r\nIf you decide to use one different than the ones mentioned make sure that it does support SSL otherwise you cannot enter the staff channel.','2012-10-23 03:38:43'),(85,1,4,'irc_chanserv',0,'09. ChanServ Commands','In depth description of ChanServ Commands','[align=center][b][size=2]ChanServ Commands[/size][/b][/align]\r\n\r\nChanServ allows you to register and control various aspects of channels. ChanServ can often prevent malicious users from â€œtaking overâ€ channels by limiting who is allowed channel operator privileges. Available commands are listed below; to use them, type [quote]/msg ChanServ command[/quote]. For more information on a specific command, type [quote]/msg ChanServ HELP command[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]REGISTER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  REGISTER channel password description\r\n \r\n Registers a channel in the ChanServ database.  In order\r\n to use this command, you must first be a channel operator\r\n on the channel you\'re trying to register.  The password\r\n is used with the IDENTIFY command to allow others to\r\n make changes to the channel settings at a later time.\r\n The last parameter, which must be included, is a\r\n general description of the channel\'s purpose.\r\n \r\n When you register a channel, you are recorded as the\r\n \"founder\" of the channel.  The channel founder is allowed\r\n to change all of the channel settings for the channel;\r\n ChanServ will also automatically give the founder\r\n channel-operator privileges when s/he enters the channel.\r\n See the ACCESS command (/msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS) for\r\n information on giving a subset of these privileges to\r\n other channel users.\r\n \r\n NOTICE: In order to register a channel, you must have\r\n first registered your nickname.  If you haven\'t,\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP for information on how to do so.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]IDENTIFY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  IDENTIFY channel password\r\n \r\n Authenticates you to ChanServ as the founder of the given\r\n channel.  Many commands require you to use this command\r\n before using them.  The password should be the same one\r\n you sent with the REGISTER command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LOGOUT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  LOGOUT channel nickname\r\n \r\n This command will log the selected nickname out meaning they\r\n would have to reidentify themselves to regain their access.\r\n \r\n If you are the founder of the channel, you can log out anybody,\r\n else you can only log out yourself.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DROP[/b]\r\n[/quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ DROP channel\r\n \r\n Unregisters the named channel.  Can only be used by\r\n channel founder, who must use the IDENTIFY command first.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel option parameters\r\n \r\n Allows the channel founder to set various channel options\r\n and other information.\r\n \r\n Available options:\r\n \r\n     FOUNDER       Set the founder of a channel\r\n     SUCCESSOR     Set the successor for a channel\r\n     PASSWORD      Set the founder password\r\n     DESC          Set the channel description\r\n     URL           Associate a URL with the channel\r\n     EMAIL         Associate an E-mail address with the channel\r\n     ENTRYMSG      Set a message to be sent to users when they\r\n                      enter the channel\r\n     BANTYPE       Set how Services make bans on the channel\r\n     MLOCK         Lock channel modes on or off\r\n     KEEPTOPIC     Retain topic when channel is not in use\r\n     OPNOTICE      Send a notice when OP/DEOP commands are used\r\n     PEACE         Regulate the use of critical commands\r\n     PRIVATE       Hide channel from LIST command\r\n     RESTRICTED    Restrict access to the channel\r\n     SECURE        Activate ChanServ security features\r\n     SECUREOPS     Stricter control of chanop status\r\n     SECUREFOUNDER Stricter control of channel founder status\r\n     SIGNKICK      Sign kicks that are done with KICK command\r\n     TOPICLOCK     Topic can only be changed with TOPIC\r\n     XOP           Toggle the user privilege system\r\n \r\n Type /msg ChanServ HELP SET option for more information on a\r\n particular option.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET FOUNDER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel FOUNDER nick\r\n \r\n Changes the founder of a channel.  The new nickname must\r\n be a registered one.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SUCCESSOR[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SUCCESSOR nick\r\n \r\n Changes the successor of a channel.  If the founder\'s\r\n nickname expires or is dropped while the channel is still\r\n registered, the successor will become the new founder of the\r\n channel.  However, if the successor already has too many\r\n channels registered (<num>), the channel will be dropped\r\n instead, just as if no successor had been set.  The new\r\n nickname must be a registered one.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET PASSWORD[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PASSWORD password\r\n \r\n Sets the password used to identify as the founder of the\r\n channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET DESC[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel DESC description\r\n \r\n Sets the description for the channel, which shows up with\r\n the LIST and INFO commands.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET URL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel URL <url>\r\n \r\n Associates the given URL with the channel.  This URL will\r\n be displayed whenever someone requests information on the\r\n channel with the INFO command.  If no parameter is given,\r\n deletes any current URL for the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET EMAIL[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel EMAIL [address]\r\n \r\n Associates the given E-mail address with the channel.\r\n This address will be displayed whenever someone requests\r\n information on the channel with the INFO command.  If no\r\n parameter is given, deletes any current E-mail address for\r\n the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET ENTRYMSG[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel ENTRYMSG [message]\r\n \r\n Sets the message which will be sent via /notice to users\r\n when they enter the channel.  If no parameter is given,\r\n causes no message to be sent upon entering the channel.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET BANTYPE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel BANTYPE bantype\r\n \r\n Sets the ban type that will be used by services whenever\r\n they need to ban someone from your channel.\r\n \r\n bantype is a number between 0 and 3 that means:\r\n \r\n 0: ban in the form *!user@host\r\n 1: ban in the form *!*user@host\r\n 2: ban in the form *!*@host\r\n 3: ban in the form *!*user@*.domain[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET KEEPTOPIC[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel KEEPTOPIC {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the topic retention option for a\r\n channel.  When topic retention is set, the topic for the\r\n channel will be remembered by ChanServ even after the\r\n last user leaves the channel, and will be restored the\r\n next time the channel is created.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]SET TOPICLOCK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel TOPICLOCK {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the topic lock option for a channel.\r\n When topic lock is set, ChanServ will not allow the\r\n channel topic to be changed except via the TOPIC\r\n command.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET MLOCK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel MLOCK modes\r\n \r\n Sets the mode-lock parameter for the channel. ChanServ\r\n allows you to define certain channel modes to be always\r\n on, off or free to be either on or off.\r\n \r\n The modes parameter is constructed exactly the same way\r\n as a /MODE command; that is, modes followed by a + are\r\n locked on, and modes followed by a - are locked off. Note,\r\n however, that unlike the /MODE command, each use of\r\n SET MLOCK will remove all modes previously locked before\r\n setting the new!\r\n \r\n Warning:  If you set a mode-locked key, as in the second\r\n example below, you should also set the RESTRICTED option for\r\n the channel (see HELP SET RESTRICTED), or anyone entering\r\n the channel when it is empty will be able to see the key!\r\n \r\n Examples:\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +nt-iklps\r\n         Forces modes n and t on, and modes i, k, l, p, and\r\n         s off.  Mode m is left free to be either on or off.\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +knst-ilmp my-key\r\n         Forces modes k, n, s, and t on, and modes i, l, m,\r\n         and p off.  Also forces the channel key to be\r\n         \"my-key\".\r\n \r\n     SET #channel MLOCK +\r\n         Removes the mode lock; all channel modes are free\r\n         to be either on or off.\r\n		 [/quote]\r\n[b]SET PEACE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PEACE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the peace option for a channel.\r\n When peace is set, an user won\'t be able to kick,\r\n ban or remove a channel status of an user that has\r\n a level superior or equal to his via ChanServ commands.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET PRIVATE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel PRIVATE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the private option for a channel.\r\n When private is set, a /msg ChanServ LIST will not\r\n include the channel in any lists.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET RESTRICTED[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel RESTRICTED {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the restricted access option for a\r\n channel.  When restricted access is set, users not on\r\n the access list will instead be kicked and banned from the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECURE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECURE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables ChanServ\'s security features for a\r\n channel.  When SECURE is set, only users who have\r\n registered their nicknames with ChanServ and IDENTIFY\'d\r\n with their password will be given access to the channel\r\n as controlled by the access list.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECUREOPS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECUREOPS {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the secure ops option for a channel.\r\n When secure ops is set, users who are not on the userlist\r\n will not be allowed chanop status.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SECUREFOUNDER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SECUREFOUNDER {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the secure founder option for a channel.\r\n When secure founder is set, only the real founder will be\r\n able to drop the channel, change its password, its founder and its\r\n successor, and not those who are IDENTIFY\'d with ChanServ.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET SIGNKICK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel SIGNKICK {ON | LEVEL | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables signed kicks for a\r\n channel.  When SIGNKICK is set, kicks issued with\r\n ChanServ KICK command will have the nick that used the\r\n command in their reason.\r\n \r\n If you use LEVEL, those who have a level that is superior\r\n or equal to the SIGNKICK level on the channel won\'t have their\r\n kicks signed. See /msg ChanServ HELP LEVELS for more information.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET XOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel XOP {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the xOP lists system for a channel.\r\n When XOP is set, you have to use the AOP/SOP/VOP\r\n commands in order to give channel privileges to\r\n users, else you have to use the ACCESS command.\r\n \r\n Technical Note: when you switch from access list to xOP\r\n lists system, your level definitions and user levels will be\r\n changed, so you won\'t find the same values if you\r\n switch back to access system!\r\n \r\n You should also check that your users are in the good xOP\r\n list after the switch from access to xOP lists, because the\r\n guess is not always perfect... in fact, it is not recommended\r\n to use the xOP lists if you changed level definitions with\r\n the LEVELS command.\r\n \r\n Switching from xOP lists system to access list system\r\n causes no problem though.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SET OPNOTICE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SET channel OPNOTICE {ON | OFF}\r\n \r\n Enables or disables the op-notice option for a channel.\r\n When op-notice is set, ChanServ will send a notice to the\r\n channel whenever the OP or DEOP commands are used for a user\r\n in the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]AOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  AOP channel ADD nick\r\n         AOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         AOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         AOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the AOP (AutoOP) list for a channel. The AOP\r\n list gives users the right to be auto-opped on your channel,\r\n to unban or invite themselves if needed, to have their\r\n greet message showed on join, and so on.\r\n \r\n The AOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n AOP list.\r\n \r\n The AOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n AOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The AOP LIST command displays the AOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    AOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists AOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The AOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n AOP list.\r\n \r\n The AOP ADD and AOP DEL commands are limited to\r\n SOPs or above, while the AOP CLEAR command can only\r\n be used by the channel founder. However, any user on the\r\n AOP list may use the AOP LIST command.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]HOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  HOP channel ADD nick\r\n         HOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         HOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         HOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the HOP (HalfOP) list for a channel. The HOP\r\n list gives users the right to be auto-halfopped on your\r\n channel.\r\n \r\n The HOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n HOP list.\r\n \r\n The HOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n HOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The HOP LIST command displays the HOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    HOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists HOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The HOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n HOP list.\r\n \r\n The HOP ADD, HOP DEL and HOP LIST commands are\r\n limited to AOPs or above, while the HOP CLEAR command\r\n can only be used by the channel founder.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]SOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  SOP channel ADD nick\r\n         SOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         SOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         SOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the SOP (SuperOP) list for a channel. The SOP\r\n list gives users all rights given by the AOP list, and adds\r\n those needed to use the AutoKick and the BadWords lists,\r\n to send and read channel memos, and so on.\r\n \r\n The SOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n SOP list.\r\n \r\n The SOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n SOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The SOP LIST command displays the SOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    SOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists AOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The SOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n SOP list.\r\n \r\n The SOP ADD, SOP DEL and SOP CLEAR commands are\r\n limited to the channel founder. However, any user on the\r\n AOP list may use the SOP LIST command.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]VOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  VOP channel ADD nick\r\n         VOP channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         VOP channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         VOP channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the VOP (VOicePeople) list for a channel.\r\n The VOP list allows users to be auto-voiced and to voice\r\n themselves if they aren\'t.\r\n \r\n The VOP ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n VOP list.\r\n \r\n The VOP DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n VOP list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The VOP LIST command displays the VOP list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    VOP #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists VOP entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The VOP CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n VOP list.\r\n \r\n The VOP ADD, VOP DEL and VOP LIST commands are\r\n limited to AOPs or above, while the VOP CLEAR command\r\n can only be used by the channel founder.\r\n \r\n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\r\n in that case you need to use the access list. See\r\n /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS for information about the access list,\r\n and /msg ChanServ HELP SET XOP to know how to toggle between\r\n the access list and xOP list systems.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]ACCESS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  ACCESS channel ADD nick level\r\n         ACCESS channel DEL {nick | entry-num | list}\r\n         ACCESS channel LIST [mask | list]\r\n         ACCESS channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the access list for a channel.  The access\r\n list specifies which users are allowed chanop status or\r\n access to ChanServ commands on the channel.  Different\r\n user levels allow for access to different subsets of\r\n privileges; /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more\r\n specific information.  Any nick not on the access list has\r\n a user level of 0.\r\n \r\n The ACCESS ADD command adds the given nickname to the\r\n access list with the given user level; if the nick is\r\n already present on the list, its access level is changed to\r\n the level specified in the command.  The level specified\r\n must be less than that of the user giving the command, and\r\n if the nick is already on the access list, the current\r\n access level of that nick must be less than the access level\r\n of the user giving the command.\r\n \r\n The ACCESS DEL command removes the given nick from the\r\n access list.  If a list of entry numbers is given, those\r\n entries are deleted.  (See the example for LIST below.)\r\n \r\n The ACCESS LIST command displays the access list.  If\r\n a wildcard mask is given, only those entries matching the\r\n mask are displayed.  If a list of entry numbers is given,\r\n only those entries are shown; for example:\r\n\r\n    ACCESS #channel LIST 2-5,7-9\r\n       Lists access entries numbered 2 through 5 and\r\n       7 through 9.\r\n \r\n The ACCESS CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n access list.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]ACCESS LEVELS[/b]\r\n[quote] User access levels\r\n \r\n By default, the following access levels are defined:\r\n \r\n    Founder   Full access to ChanServ functions; automatic\r\n                      opping upon entering channel.  Note\r\n                      that only one person may have founder\r\n                      status (it can be given using the\r\n                      ACCESS command and using level 9999).\r\n         10   Access to AKICK command; automatic opping.\r\n          5   Automatic opping.\r\n          3   Automatic voicing.\r\n          0   No special privileges; can be opped by other\r\n                      ops (unless secure-ops is set).\r\n         <0   May not be opped.\r\n \r\n These levels may be changed, or new ones added, using the\r\n LEVELS command; type /msg ChanServ HELP LEVELS for\r\n information.[/quote]\r\n\r\n[b]AKICK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  AKICK channel ADD {nick | mask} [reason]\r\n         AKICK channel STICK mask\r\n         AKICK channel UNSTICK mask\r\n         AKICK channel DEL {nick | mask | entry-num | list}\r\n         AKICK channel LIST [mask | entry-num | list]\r\n         AKICK channel VIEW [mask | entry-num | list]\r\n         AKICK channel ENFORCE\r\n         AKICK channel CLEAR\r\n \r\n Maintains the AutoKick list for a channel.  If a user\r\n on the AutoKick list attempts to join the channel,\r\n ChanServ will ban that user from the channel, then kick\r\n the user.\r\n \r\n The AKICK ADD command adds the given nick or usermask\r\n to the AutoKick list.  If a reason is given with\r\n the command, that reason will be used when the user is\r\n kicked; if not, the default reason is \"You have been\r\n banned from the channel\".\r\n When akicking a registered nick the nickserv account\r\n will be added to the akick list instead of the mask.\r\n All users within that nickgroup will then be akicked.\r\n \r\n The AKICK STICK command permanently bans the given mask\r\n on the channel. If someone tries to remove the ban, ChanServ\r\n will automatically set it again. You can\'t use it for\r\n registered nicks.\r\n \r\n The AKICK UNSTICK command cancels the effect of the\r\n AKICK STICK command, so you\'ll be able to unset the\r\n ban again on the channel.\r\n \r\n The AKICK DEL command removes the given nick or mask\r\n from the AutoKick list.  It does not, however, remove any\r\n bans placed by an AutoKick; those must be removed\r\n manually.\r\n \r\n The AKICK LIST command displays the AutoKick list, or\r\n optionally only those AutoKick entries which match the\r\n given mask.\r\n \r\n The AKICK VIEW command is a more verbose version of\r\n AKICK LIST command.\r\n \r\n The AKICK ENFORCE command causes ChanServ to enforce the\r\n current AKICK list by removing those users who match an\r\n AKICK mask.\r\n \r\n The AKICK CLEAR command clears all entries of the\r\n akick list.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LEVELS[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  LEVELS channel SET type level\r\n         LEVELS channel {DIS | DISABLE} type\r\n         LEVELS channel LIST\r\n         LEVELS channel RESET\r\n \r\n The LEVELS command allows fine control over the meaning of\r\n the numeric access levels used for channels.  With this\r\n command, you can define the access level required for most\r\n of ChanServ\'s functions.  (The SET FOUNDER and SET PASSWORD\r\n commands, as well as this command, are always restricted to\r\n the channel founder.)\r\n \r\n LEVELS SET allows the access level for a function or group of\r\n functions to be changed.  LEVELS DISABLE (or DIS for short)\r\n disables an automatic feature or disallows access to a\r\n function by anyone other than the channel founder.\r\n LEVELS LIST shows the current levels for each function or\r\n group of functions.  LEVELS RESET resets the levels to the\r\n default levels of a newly-created channel (see\r\n HELP ACCESS LEVELS).\r\n \r\n For a list of the features and functions whose levels can be\r\n set, see HELP LEVELS DESC.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]INFO[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  INFO channel [ALL]\r\n \r\n Lists information about the named registered channel,\r\n including its founder, time of registration, last time\r\n used, description, and mode lock, if any. If ALL is\r\n specified, the entry message and successor will also\r\n be displayed.\r\n \r\n By default, the ALL option is limited to those with\r\n founder access on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]LIST[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  LIST pattern\r\n \r\n Lists all registered channels matching the given pattern.\r\n (Channels with the PRIVATE option set are not listed.)\r\n Note that a preceding \'#\' specifies a range, channel names\r\n are to be written without \'#\'.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]OP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  OP [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Ops a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will op you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will op you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DEOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  DEOP [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Deops a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will deop you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will deop you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]VOICE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  VOICE [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Voices a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will voice you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will voice you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel, or to VOPs or those with level 3\r\n and above for self voicing.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DEVOICE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  DEVOICE [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Devoices a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will devoice you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will devoice you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel, or to VOPs or those with level 3\r\n and above for self devoicing.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]HALFOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  HALFOP [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Halfops a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will halfop you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will halfop you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs and those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel, or to HOPs or those with level 4\r\n and above for self halfopping.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DEHALFOP[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  DEHALFOP [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Dehalfops a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will dehalfop you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will dehalfop you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs and those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel, or to HOPs or those with level 4\r\n and above for self dehalfopping.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]PROTECT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  PROTECT [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Protects a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will protect you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will protect you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to the founder, or to SOPs or those with\r\n level 10 and above on the channel for self protecting.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DEPROTECT[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  DEPROTECT [#channel [nick]]\r\n \r\n Deprotects a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will deprotect you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will deprotect you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to the founder, or to SOPs or those with\r\n level 10 and above on the channel for self deprotecting.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]OWNER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  OWNER [#channel]\r\n \r\n Gives you owner status on channel. If channel is not\r\n given, it will give you owner status on all channels you\'re\r\n on, provided you have the rights to.\r\n \r\n Limited to those with founder access on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]DEOWNER[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  DEOWNER [#channel]\r\n \r\n Removes your owner status on channel. If channel is\r\n not given, it will remove your owner status on all channels\r\n you\'re on, provided you have the rights to.\r\n \r\n Limited to those with founder access on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]INVITE[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  INVITE channel\r\n \r\n Tells ChanServ to invite you into the given channel.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 and above\r\n on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]UNBAN[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  UNBAN channel\r\n \r\n Tells ChanServ to remove all bans preventing you from\r\n entering the given channel.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 and above\r\n on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]KICK[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  KICK [#channel [nick [reason]]]\r\n \r\n Kicks a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will kick you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will kick you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]BAN[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  BAN [#channel [nick [reason]]]\r\n \r\n Bans a selected nick on a channel. If nick is not given,\r\n it will ban you. If channel and nick are not given,\r\n it will ban you on all channels you\'re on, provided you\r\n have the rights to.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to AOPs or those with level 5 access\r\n and above on the channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]TOPIC[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  TOPIC channel [topic]\r\n \r\n Causes ChanServ to set the channel topic to the one\r\n specified. If topic is not given, then an empty topic\r\n is set. This command is most useful in conjunction\r\n with SET TOPICLOCK. See /msg ChanServ HELP SET TOPICLOCK\r\n for more information.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to those with founder access on the\r\n channel. [/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]CLEAR[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  CLEAR channel what\r\n \r\n Tells ChanServ to clear certain settings on a channel.  what\r\n can be any of the following:\r\n \r\n      MODES    Resets all modes on the channel (i.e. clears\r\n                   modes i,k,l,m,n,p,s,t).\r\n      BANS     Clears all bans on the channel.\r\n      EXCEPTS  Clears all excepts on the channel.\r\n      INVITES  Clears all invites on the channel.\r\n      OPS      Removes channel-operator status (mode +o) from\r\n                   all channel operators.\r\n      HOPS     Removes channel-halfoperator status (mode +h) from\r\n                   all channel halfoperators, if supported.\r\n      VOICES   Removes \"voice\" status (mode +v) from anyone\r\n                   with that mode set.\r\n      USERS    Removes (kicks) all users from the channel.\r\n \r\n By default, limited to those with founder access on the\r\n channel.[/quote]\r\n \r\n[b]GETKEY[/b]\r\n[quote] Syntax: /msg ChanServ  GETKEY channel\r\n \r\n Returns the key of the given channel. This is a command\r\n mainly intended to be used by bots and/or scripts, so\r\n the output is in the following way:\r\n \r\n KEY <channel> <key>\r\n \r\n key is \"NO KEY\" if no key is set.[/quote]','2012-09-11 15:40:37'),(86,1,8,'modmanual',500,'The ModManual','A guide for staff on how to apply the rules day to day','\r\n[size=3][color=#FF0000]<< insert modmanual here >>[/color][/size]','2012-09-11 22:26:55'),(87,1,8,'stafftools',500,'Staff Tools','How to use the staff tools','\r\n[size=3][color=#FF0000]<< insert guide to staff tools here >>[/color][/size]\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=mfs]Marked for deletion[/#]\r\nblah blah blah\r\n\r\n[#=reportsv2]Handling torrent reports (the reportsv2 system)[/#]\r\nblah blah blah\r\n\r\n[#=userpage]User page[/#]\r\nblah blah blah\r\n\r\n\r\n','2012-09-11 23:03:31'),(88,1,8,'newstaff',500,'Staff 101','What you need to know as a new staff','\r\n[size=2][color=#FF0000]<< Just an idea but this might be useful ?? >>\r\n\r\n<< PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CONTRIBUTE TO THIS ARTICLE - this is just a stub >>[/color][/size]\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=day2day]day to day tasks[/#]\r\n\r\n[*]answering messages sent to staff - use the common responses where possible\r\n[*]dealing with reports\r\n[*]checking torrents\r\n[*]moderating forums\r\n\r\n\r\n[#=stuff]stuff you should know[/#]\r\n\r\n[*]We do not record the ip\'s of staff: your ip will appear as 127.0.0.1 to the site \r\n[*]<< PFL policy >>\r\n[*]You represent empornium to the users, try and deal with them in a professional way (even when they are dicks)\r\n[*]try and apply the rules in a way consistent with the other staff (see [url=/articles.php?topic=modmanual]the ModManual[/url] for details)\r\n[*]staff decisions are made in the staff forum, we are generally democratic-ish in that staff decisions are usually talked about before they are made - ultimately staff policy is set by the senior staff (usually with consensus, or majority vote, occasionally by dictat)\r\n\r\n','2012-09-11 23:04:27');
